00:01:35.680 --> 00:01:38.710
This series aims to have open
and constructive conversations

00:01:38.710 --> 00:01:42.340
on race and capturing the full
breadth of being Hispanic,

00:01:42.340 --> 00:01:44.740
or Latinx, in
America, incorporates

00:01:44.740 --> 00:01:48.940
notions of race, ethnicity,
culture, language, emotive

00:01:48.940 --> 00:01:52.180
attachments and
affiliations, for starters.

00:01:52.180 --> 00:01:55.474
Defining the Hispanic
Latino identity is complex.

00:01:55.474 --> 00:01:56.890
With all of that
in mind, I'd like

00:01:56.890 --> 00:01:59.230
to start by asking
our panelists,

00:01:59.230 --> 00:02:02.830
what does it mean to be
Hispanic, Latinx in the US,

00:02:02.830 --> 00:02:09.020
and what is a responsible way
to grapple with that complexity?

00:02:09.020 --> 00:02:11.070
AMERICA FERRERA: I
guess I'll start.

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:14.770
I just learned
that I'm a Latinx.

00:02:14.770 --> 00:02:16.000
I just learned that term.

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:20.520
I didn't really know what it
meant until someone told me.

00:02:20.520 --> 00:02:23.710
And, you know, I mean,
I can really only

00:02:23.710 --> 00:02:26.530
speak for my own personal
experience and the sort

00:02:26.530 --> 00:02:30.460
of anecdotal experiences
and conversations

00:02:30.460 --> 00:02:36.640
I've had with other
Latino Americans.

00:02:36.640 --> 00:02:39.670
It is-- for me, it's
been one of the biggest

00:02:39.670 --> 00:02:40.660
questions of my life.

00:02:40.660 --> 00:02:43.840
I was born in Los Angeles,
raised in the San Fernando

00:02:43.840 --> 00:02:46.690
Valley to immigrant parents.

00:02:46.690 --> 00:02:54.370
And I grew up mainly
surrounded by Jewish people.

00:02:54.370 --> 00:02:57.860
So a big, big part of me
feels Jewish, culturally.

00:02:57.860 --> 00:02:59.360
Never went to a
single quinceanera--

00:02:59.360 --> 00:03:01.690
tons of bar and bat mitzvahs.

00:03:01.690 --> 00:03:03.880
And I remember going
to school, and most

00:03:03.880 --> 00:03:08.590
of the Latinos I would encounter
were bused in from downtown.

00:03:08.590 --> 00:03:12.580
And I had been sort of--

00:03:12.580 --> 00:03:15.400
through family, through
culture, through just observing

00:03:15.400 --> 00:03:17.110
the world around me--

00:03:17.110 --> 00:03:21.490
kind of conditioned to
think of myself as outside

00:03:21.490 --> 00:03:23.151
of that Latino.

00:03:23.151 --> 00:03:23.650
You know?

00:03:23.650 --> 00:03:27.820
I wanted to be
academically successful.

00:03:27.820 --> 00:03:29.950
I wanted to be top of my class.

00:03:29.950 --> 00:03:31.030
I wanted to succeed.

00:03:31.030 --> 00:03:32.200
I had big ambitions.

00:03:32.200 --> 00:03:35.230
And everything and everyone
around me, you know,

00:03:35.230 --> 00:03:38.999
reminded me that I couldn't
be that kind of Latino

00:03:38.999 --> 00:03:40.540
if I wanted to be
and do the things I

00:03:40.540 --> 00:03:41.623
wanted to do in the world.

00:03:41.623 --> 00:03:47.020
And so a lot of my
young Latino identity

00:03:47.020 --> 00:03:51.160
really had a lot to do
with neglecting and denying

00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:53.230
my Latino identity.

00:03:53.230 --> 00:03:55.840
And that was a really,
really complicated thing.

00:03:55.840 --> 00:03:59.830
To find success as an actress,
be immediately labeled

00:03:59.830 --> 00:04:02.650
and deemed a Latina
actress, held up

00:04:02.650 --> 00:04:05.800
as a representative of
the Latino community,

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:08.380
when my dirty, dirty secret
on the inside was like,

00:04:08.380 --> 00:04:12.940
I don't know what it means,
to me, to be a Latina.

00:04:12.940 --> 00:04:15.370
And so I had to go on
that journey for myself

00:04:15.370 --> 00:04:18.970
to figure that out and
give myself the permission

00:04:18.970 --> 00:04:23.750
to claim my Latino identity
and to define it for myself.

00:04:23.750 --> 00:04:29.380
And while every young Latino
or Latinx's experiences

00:04:29.380 --> 00:04:35.050
is quite different, what I
think is the common thread, when

00:04:35.050 --> 00:04:38.850
you're a Latin American,
is that you're sort of--

00:04:38.850 --> 00:04:42.790
you're charged with this
question of are you an American

00:04:42.790 --> 00:04:43.820
or are you a Latina?

00:04:43.820 --> 00:04:45.340
And what is the line?

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:46.630
And how much of you is this?

00:04:46.630 --> 00:04:48.340
And how much of you is that?

00:04:48.340 --> 00:04:51.460
And what I can say is
that, you can't be a Latinx

00:04:51.460 --> 00:04:55.120
without having to ask yourself
those questions almost

00:04:55.120 --> 00:04:55.990
on a daily basis.

00:04:57.793 --> 00:04:59.668
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO:
Thanks for sharing that.

00:04:59.668 --> 00:05:01.251
[INAUDIBLE] would
you like to go next?

00:05:01.251 --> 00:05:03.460
I'm sorry, I saw you
go to your microphone.

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:05.092
RHONDA GONZALEZ: You go first.

00:05:05.092 --> 00:05:07.300
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: That's
a very interesting story.

00:05:07.300 --> 00:05:08.770
Thanks for sharing that.

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:13.960
I think that to be Latino is
something so exciting today.

00:05:13.960 --> 00:05:14.650
It really is.

00:05:14.650 --> 00:05:16.870
It's an exciting
time to be Latino.

00:05:16.870 --> 00:05:19.090
I feel it in my soul.

00:05:19.090 --> 00:05:21.670
I mean, every time I
pick up a newspaper,

00:05:21.670 --> 00:05:24.970
every time I go online,
every time I turn the TV on,

00:05:24.970 --> 00:05:27.110
there is something happening.

00:05:27.110 --> 00:05:30.460
There is a discussion
as to, how can we

00:05:30.460 --> 00:05:33.560
bring this incredible group
of people into the fold?

00:05:33.560 --> 00:05:35.290
How can we
communicate with them?

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:36.670
How can we connect them?

00:05:36.670 --> 00:05:39.310
How can we get them
to vote for us?

00:05:39.310 --> 00:05:41.350
Which is where I'm coming from.

00:05:41.350 --> 00:05:42.606
We really need that vote!

00:05:42.606 --> 00:05:44.230
I mean, you look at
the numbers of what

00:05:44.230 --> 00:05:47.224
it means to be Hispanic, nearly
25% of all babies born today

00:05:47.224 --> 00:05:49.390
have some sort of Latin
American background to them.

00:05:49.390 --> 00:05:51.837
So it's an exciting
time to be Hispanic.

00:05:51.837 --> 00:05:53.170
It's an exciting group to cover.

00:05:53.170 --> 00:05:55.706
I teach the history of
the Dominican Republic

00:05:55.706 --> 00:05:57.580
at the Borough of
Manhattan Community College

00:05:57.580 --> 00:06:00.220
as well as the Latino
experience in the United States.

00:06:00.220 --> 00:06:03.220
And my classes are
filled to capacity.

00:06:03.220 --> 00:06:06.114
People of all different races
and ethnicities and backgrounds

00:06:06.114 --> 00:06:07.780
are coming in because
they want to learn

00:06:07.780 --> 00:06:11.530
more of what this dynamic
group of people are all about.

00:06:11.530 --> 00:06:13.300
One thing that many
of them don't know

00:06:13.300 --> 00:06:16.630
is that it's very complicated
to answer, even as a professor

00:06:16.630 --> 00:06:17.730
standing before them.

00:06:17.730 --> 00:06:18.730
What is a Latino?

00:06:18.730 --> 00:06:20.590
What is a Latino supposed to be?

00:06:20.590 --> 00:06:22.100
What does a Latino look like?

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:24.940
What kind of a racial
background does a Latino claim?

00:06:24.940 --> 00:06:26.920
And it is something that
is very complicated,

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:30.220
and it's something that I
think needs to be understood.

00:06:30.220 --> 00:06:31.345
It needs to be appreciated.

00:06:31.345 --> 00:06:33.460
It needs to be read about.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:35.430
And you need to
somehow delve yourself

00:06:35.430 --> 00:06:39.520
in the history of Latin American
United States relations.

00:06:39.520 --> 00:06:41.140
I think that it's
important for people

00:06:41.140 --> 00:06:43.254
like President Trump,
and people in the House

00:06:43.254 --> 00:06:45.670
of Representatives, as we
talked earlier, people in the US

00:06:45.670 --> 00:06:47.710
Senate, to stop for a
minute to really study

00:06:47.710 --> 00:06:50.557
the history of what it
is to be a Latin American

00:06:50.557 --> 00:06:53.140
and understand the United States
involvement in Latin America.

00:06:53.140 --> 00:06:55.390
To understand how we
came to be, and to see

00:06:55.390 --> 00:06:58.750
the complicated issues
that exist today

00:06:58.750 --> 00:07:00.190
are not just about
talking points.

00:07:00.190 --> 00:07:03.190
They really affect people, and
they're historical in nature.

00:07:03.190 --> 00:07:08.230
So to be Hispanic, to be
Latino, is to have the burden--

00:07:08.230 --> 00:07:11.380
once you're cognizant of
our history and cognizant

00:07:11.380 --> 00:07:14.980
of what we are-- it's to
have the burden of knowing

00:07:14.980 --> 00:07:17.620
that your ancestors
were rapists,

00:07:17.620 --> 00:07:21.610
and murderers, people that
enslaved millions of people.

00:07:21.610 --> 00:07:23.920
It is also to feel
the tragedy of knowing

00:07:23.920 --> 00:07:25.979
that your ancestors were
the enslaved ones-- were

00:07:25.979 --> 00:07:27.770
the people that were
raped, were the people

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:29.680
that were brought
here in shackles.

00:07:29.680 --> 00:07:32.590
It is having the anger to know
that your people's lands were

00:07:32.590 --> 00:07:33.580
taken.

00:07:33.580 --> 00:07:36.560
It is to feel the
resentment inside your soul.

00:07:36.560 --> 00:07:38.870
To know that your
ancestors, at one point,

00:07:38.870 --> 00:07:40.519
experienced genocide.

00:07:40.519 --> 00:07:42.060
And it's having all
of that combined.

00:07:42.060 --> 00:07:43.280
That once you really
appreciate what

00:07:43.280 --> 00:07:45.030
it is to be Hispanic--
once you get closer

00:07:45.030 --> 00:07:47.150
and closer to
understanding, you begin

00:07:47.150 --> 00:07:50.210
to see how you can
become bipolar.

00:07:50.210 --> 00:07:52.940
You can have this
resentment within yourself

00:07:52.940 --> 00:07:54.230
and appreciation of yourself.

00:07:54.230 --> 00:07:56.270
And the reason I'm so
excited is because we

00:07:56.270 --> 00:07:57.790
have some panelists here
that have been focused

00:07:57.790 --> 00:07:59.364
a great deal on
this issue, bringing

00:07:59.364 --> 00:08:00.530
this issue to the forefront.

00:08:00.530 --> 00:08:02.280
I'm excited to hear
what they have to say.

00:08:02.280 --> 00:08:04.550
I'm really excited to be
part of the group here today.

00:08:04.550 --> 00:08:06.460
Because we have so many--

00:08:06.460 --> 00:08:07.650
so much diversity.

00:08:07.650 --> 00:08:09.650
We have blacks, we have
whites, we have Chinese,

00:08:09.650 --> 00:08:11.570
we have mulattoes, like me.

00:08:11.570 --> 00:08:13.280
We have hair of every texture.

00:08:13.280 --> 00:08:15.530
We have transgender, we
have gay, we have lesbian,

00:08:15.530 --> 00:08:16.545
we have straight.

00:08:16.545 --> 00:08:18.420
We have those that don't
identify or conform.

00:08:18.420 --> 00:08:19.910
So it's an exciting
time, and that's

00:08:19.910 --> 00:08:21.020
why I'm so happy to
be here, and hope

00:08:21.020 --> 00:08:22.255
we get to talk more about it.

00:08:22.255 --> 00:08:23.630
So thank you again
for having me.

00:08:23.630 --> 00:08:26.190
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

00:08:26.190 --> 00:08:27.830
ANDREW HERRERA: Awesome.

00:08:27.830 --> 00:08:29.540
Well, you know, I think it's--

00:08:29.540 --> 00:08:32.570
probably, like everyone said,
it's a very complex question.

00:08:32.570 --> 00:08:34.659
And I don't think
there's one answer.

00:08:34.659 --> 00:08:36.919
I think there's several answers.

00:08:36.919 --> 00:08:38.750
You know, the term
Latinx is something

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:41.570
that has become kind
of in vogue in terms

00:08:41.570 --> 00:08:44.450
of how to describe this
community over the last year,

00:08:44.450 --> 00:08:45.210
year and a half.

00:08:45.210 --> 00:08:47.210
I think, in the political
environment, actually,

00:08:47.210 --> 00:08:51.860
even become even a more common
way to describe this community.

00:08:51.860 --> 00:08:55.850
I think first we've got to
look back at why that is.

00:08:55.850 --> 00:08:58.250
I think, you know,
we've been trying to--

00:08:58.250 --> 00:09:02.390
first, you know, I think I
grew up in the '90s, and a lot

00:09:02.390 --> 00:09:07.780
of times it was about kind
of people calling you--

00:09:07.780 --> 00:09:10.400
you know, identifying
you as Spanish,

00:09:10.400 --> 00:09:11.840
but you're not Spanish.

00:09:11.840 --> 00:09:13.270
You know, I'm not from Spain.

00:09:13.270 --> 00:09:15.350
I'm an Ecuadorian
kid from Queens.

00:09:15.350 --> 00:09:18.050
Then, as you get
older, it's about,

00:09:18.050 --> 00:09:20.540
are you Latino or Hispanic,
and what does that mean?

00:09:20.540 --> 00:09:24.634
And then today, now when
we talk about Latinx,

00:09:24.634 --> 00:09:27.800
I don't think it's
about necessarily trying

00:09:27.800 --> 00:09:30.230
to define this
group, but actually

00:09:30.230 --> 00:09:31.400
embrace this complexity.

00:09:31.400 --> 00:09:32.850
Because it is evolving.

00:09:32.850 --> 00:09:36.330
I think, you know, I heard a
lot about kind of the history.

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:41.600
And I think history is
something we should understand,

00:09:41.600 --> 00:09:44.630
but we shouldn't
have it be what I

00:09:44.630 --> 00:09:47.170
guess narrows our thinking
about what, you know, Latinidad,

00:09:47.170 --> 00:09:49.130
or what being Latino is today.

00:09:49.130 --> 00:09:51.590
It's something that is
continually evolving,

00:09:51.590 --> 00:09:54.590
the same way being
American 100 years ago

00:09:54.590 --> 00:09:57.620
feels different than it
is to be American today.

00:09:57.620 --> 00:10:00.650
I think that's how we look
at Latinos, or our Latinx

00:10:00.650 --> 00:10:01.580
community.

00:10:01.580 --> 00:10:03.650
We're going to be
continually evolving.

00:10:06.760 --> 00:10:08.010
RHONDA GONZALEZ: That's great.

00:10:08.010 --> 00:10:12.300
So I think America and
JC and Andrew, what

00:10:12.300 --> 00:10:15.660
I hear in their conversation
is this real threat

00:10:15.660 --> 00:10:19.470
of both the individual journey
and also a national journey.

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:21.750
And then I hear a racial
journey, as well, right?

00:10:21.750 --> 00:10:23.560
So all those kind of identities.

00:10:23.560 --> 00:10:27.890
And I think that that
really does underscore,

00:10:27.890 --> 00:10:29.550
in part, the complexity of it.

00:10:29.550 --> 00:10:32.350
And then much of it-- at
least in the way I see it,

00:10:32.350 --> 00:10:34.800
and to just back up a little
bit and give a little bio.

00:10:34.800 --> 00:10:36.540
I grew up just down
the street from here,

00:10:36.540 --> 00:10:38.490
in Long Beach, California.

00:10:38.490 --> 00:10:43.170
And I grew up in a predominantly
African-American community,

00:10:43.170 --> 00:10:46.740
for the most part, and
in my earliest years

00:10:46.740 --> 00:10:49.110
felt at least an affinity.

00:10:49.110 --> 00:10:50.940
You know, when you
grow up around friends.

00:10:50.940 --> 00:10:52.890
But, you know,
along that journey,

00:10:52.890 --> 00:10:57.660
I too encountered the reality
that people sort of create

00:10:57.660 --> 00:11:01.320
paradigms that we
enter into, or we

00:11:01.320 --> 00:11:04.800
get read through these lenses
that we didn't necessarily

00:11:04.800 --> 00:11:05.400
construct.

00:11:05.400 --> 00:11:10.110
And so we're constantly aware
of negotiating all of that.

00:11:10.110 --> 00:11:12.780
And also, I think
in some ways wanting

00:11:12.780 --> 00:11:15.390
to play a role in
making sure that we

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:17.070
are constructing the ongoing--

00:11:17.070 --> 00:11:19.290
to use your term--
evolving history.

00:11:19.290 --> 00:11:23.940
So we become part of the people
who construct what that means.

00:11:23.940 --> 00:11:26.710
So I think the largest
still in our nation,

00:11:26.710 --> 00:11:28.596
like thinking about
the demographic shifts

00:11:28.596 --> 00:11:29.970
in the nation and
knowing that we

00:11:29.970 --> 00:11:33.160
are becoming more and more
Latinx, Latino, Hispanic.

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:35.160
And there's a conversation
in there, by the way,

00:11:35.160 --> 00:11:36.730
to have as well.

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:37.280
Chicana.

00:11:37.280 --> 00:11:39.450
I think we should
put that out there.

00:11:39.450 --> 00:11:43.180
Is that the changing
demographics demand, really,

00:11:43.180 --> 00:11:47.310
and really require us to
think about the real binary we

00:11:47.310 --> 00:11:49.170
work in within the nation.

00:11:49.170 --> 00:11:50.239
So that I think--

00:11:50.239 --> 00:11:51.780
I'd love to hear
the other panelists,

00:11:51.780 --> 00:11:56.130
but I think that a lot of
us in the center, brown folk

00:11:56.130 --> 00:12:00.090
really do work within
the black white binary.

00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:04.530
We live within it, and we see
that very dominant conversation

00:12:04.530 --> 00:12:05.701
happening.

00:12:05.701 --> 00:12:07.950
And then we enter it and
we're kind of like, you know,

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:08.790
we're here!

00:12:08.790 --> 00:12:12.030
We're not quite maybe what you
think of as black identified

00:12:12.030 --> 00:12:15.720
or white identified, but there's
a whole spectrum that we cover.

00:12:15.720 --> 00:12:18.630
And I think in part of moving
forward with the nation,

00:12:18.630 --> 00:12:21.540
we really do have to reckon
with that conversation

00:12:21.540 --> 00:12:26.940
and conscientiously realize that
the binaries we live within,

00:12:26.940 --> 00:12:28.900
whether they are gender--

00:12:28.900 --> 00:12:31.740
which we're really thinking
about today more than ever.

00:12:31.740 --> 00:12:35.310
We all have to think about race
and what the role of colorism

00:12:35.310 --> 00:12:38.460
has meant in not just
Latino communities,

00:12:38.460 --> 00:12:40.592
but across communities.

00:12:40.592 --> 00:12:42.300
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you so much.

00:12:42.300 --> 00:12:45.120
There's so much to
uncover from everything

00:12:45.120 --> 00:12:47.370
that you've all shared.

00:12:47.370 --> 00:12:50.910
I want to touch several
points that you just

00:12:50.910 --> 00:12:54.480
made, Rhonda, but I want
to touch on the labels

00:12:54.480 --> 00:12:56.276
and how we identify ourselves.

00:12:56.276 --> 00:12:57.900
America, you started
by saying you just

00:12:57.900 --> 00:12:59.780
found out you're Latinx.

00:12:59.780 --> 00:13:02.040
I grew up in the
Dominican Republic,

00:13:02.040 --> 00:13:04.451
and I became Hispanic when
I moved to the States.

00:13:04.451 --> 00:13:04.950
You know?

00:13:04.950 --> 00:13:07.260
So a lot of us are grappling
with identities that are

00:13:07.260 --> 00:13:09.600
evolving and shifting often.

00:13:09.600 --> 00:13:16.140
So Latinx, Hispanic, Chicana,
Latino, Latin American.

00:13:16.140 --> 00:13:18.260
What is the term, if
there is only one?

00:13:18.260 --> 00:13:21.000
And when you speak of it,
what are the terms that you

00:13:21.000 --> 00:13:23.130
recommend to others?

00:13:23.130 --> 00:13:25.410
How do you identify
yourself, and how do you

00:13:25.410 --> 00:13:28.992
speak to others about what
these terms and labels mean?

00:13:28.992 --> 00:13:31.700
ANDREW HERRERA: We'll
go to you, America.

00:13:31.700 --> 00:13:33.360
AMERICA FERRERA: I
have to start again?

00:13:33.360 --> 00:13:34.420
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Let's start over here now.

00:13:34.420 --> 00:13:36.461
AMERICA FERRERA: Let's
start with the professors.

00:13:36.461 --> 00:13:38.370
[LAUGHTER]

00:13:41.190 --> 00:13:42.339
ANDREW HERRERA: Sure.

00:13:42.339 --> 00:13:43.380
You know, I don't think--

00:13:43.380 --> 00:13:44.940
I don't know if
that's fair, right?

00:13:44.940 --> 00:13:48.450
I think it means something
different to each individual.

00:13:48.450 --> 00:13:52.200
I think, you know, I
started a publication that

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:56.160
was focused on breaking
stereotypes around culture

00:13:56.160 --> 00:13:58.440
and showing the evolution
and the emerging

00:13:58.440 --> 00:14:00.870
side of Latin culture.

00:14:00.870 --> 00:14:04.560
And as this has
grown over time, we

00:14:04.560 --> 00:14:08.550
see that people are coming up
with new references in terms

00:14:08.550 --> 00:14:11.310
of how they view their
generation in this community.

00:14:11.310 --> 00:14:16.720
So I think it means different
things to different people.

00:14:16.720 --> 00:14:20.400
And, for example,
editorially, you know, I--

00:14:20.400 --> 00:14:23.910
we don't call everything
Latinx, right?

00:14:23.910 --> 00:14:26.850
We look at how people
identify themselves.

00:14:26.850 --> 00:14:28.920
And this is an
argument that I think

00:14:28.920 --> 00:14:31.440
we see when we write articles.

00:14:31.440 --> 00:14:34.310
And I think, you know, the
same way America talked about--

00:14:34.310 --> 00:14:36.247
she just learned about Latinx--

00:14:36.247 --> 00:14:37.830
there is a little
bit of a frustration

00:14:37.830 --> 00:14:40.140
with a certain
generation of not wanting

00:14:40.140 --> 00:14:41.580
to be identified as Latinx.

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:44.020
Because they don't
understand it.

00:14:44.020 --> 00:14:47.850
And so I think it's not
fair to kind of force people

00:14:47.850 --> 00:14:50.380
to take on a term
about who they are,

00:14:50.380 --> 00:14:52.410
whether they were
Hispanic for one decade,

00:14:52.410 --> 00:14:57.370
and then Latinos for another,
and Latinx in this era.

00:14:57.370 --> 00:15:00.640
So I think we need to allow
it to continue to evolve.

00:15:00.640 --> 00:15:02.970
And, you know, there's--

00:15:02.970 --> 00:15:06.510
I run a company with
people that come

00:15:06.510 --> 00:15:10.290
to work because they are looking
to find a place where they're

00:15:10.290 --> 00:15:11.590
not trying to be defined.

00:15:11.590 --> 00:15:16.680
But their complexity
is part of kind

00:15:16.680 --> 00:15:18.570
of the mission of the company.

00:15:18.570 --> 00:15:19.680
So whether you're--

00:15:19.680 --> 00:15:23.790
I think, in the past, we
would look at last names

00:15:23.790 --> 00:15:26.010
as a way to identify whether
someone was Hispanic.

00:15:26.010 --> 00:15:27.840
But now you have
people that, you know,

00:15:27.840 --> 00:15:31.350
you could be Amanda Jones,
but you could actually

00:15:31.350 --> 00:15:35.500
be a Colombian or a Mexican.

00:15:35.500 --> 00:15:38.040
And so I think we
need to break away

00:15:38.040 --> 00:15:39.840
from trying to kind
of, I think, answer

00:15:39.840 --> 00:15:44.190
questions in this way, that try
to define a group in one way.

00:15:44.190 --> 00:15:48.135
So, you know, I think allowing
people to create terms.

00:15:48.135 --> 00:15:49.260
I think it's not about one.

00:15:49.260 --> 00:15:51.468
I think it's about probably
having an infinite amount

00:15:51.468 --> 00:15:54.570
of terms that allow
people to communicate

00:15:54.570 --> 00:15:56.850
their individualism.

00:15:56.850 --> 00:15:57.900
And that's what we--

00:15:57.900 --> 00:15:59.880
I think as a
community, we almost

00:15:59.880 --> 00:16:02.280
need to get out of
having these labels.

00:16:02.280 --> 00:16:04.560
Because I think it is a
certain form of conditioning.

00:16:04.560 --> 00:16:07.170
Whether it be a census
form, or whether it

00:16:07.170 --> 00:16:11.490
be identifying whether you are
part of a race or ethnicity,

00:16:11.490 --> 00:16:15.360
I think it's something that is
not in the hands of, you know,

00:16:15.360 --> 00:16:15.960
someone else.

00:16:15.960 --> 00:16:17.712
It's something that
comes from within.

00:16:17.712 --> 00:16:19.170
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Centering on

00:16:19.170 --> 00:16:20.376
your own individual identity.

00:16:20.376 --> 00:16:20.762
ANDREW HERRERA: Yeah.

00:16:20.762 --> 00:16:21.150
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

00:16:21.150 --> 00:16:23.089
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: I think--

00:16:23.089 --> 00:16:23.880
that's interesting.

00:16:23.880 --> 00:16:25.500
I think labels are important.

00:16:25.500 --> 00:16:28.560
I think we use the term
labels, and somehow we

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:31.950
want to take away
from how important

00:16:31.950 --> 00:16:34.000
what you identify as is.

00:16:34.000 --> 00:16:36.220
It's not just a word that
you just throw around.

00:16:36.220 --> 00:16:39.480
When you claim a word and you
identify as what you believe

00:16:39.480 --> 00:16:40.840
that word to be, it matters.

00:16:40.840 --> 00:16:41.790
It means something.

00:16:41.790 --> 00:16:44.150
There's a lot of
meaning behind it.

00:16:44.150 --> 00:16:47.119
So I'm very concerned.

00:16:47.119 --> 00:16:48.660
Because I think that
these labels are

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:52.020
so important that when
you introduce new labels,

00:16:52.020 --> 00:16:54.570
you tend to create
new identities,

00:16:54.570 --> 00:16:58.320
or you create an environment
where the issues that

00:16:58.320 --> 00:17:01.560
are affecting the people that
are grouped in that identity

00:17:01.560 --> 00:17:04.980
have a situation where the
real issues that impact

00:17:04.980 --> 00:17:06.960
them are diluted.

00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:09.540
Today, we have
focused a great deal

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:11.920
on changing what we identify as.

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:14.730
So today-- there was a time
when you were Hispanic.

00:17:14.730 --> 00:17:16.230
And you mentioned something
interesting about growing up

00:17:16.230 --> 00:17:17.313
in the Dominican Republic.

00:17:17.313 --> 00:17:18.910
I'm a Dominican
kid from the Bronx.

00:17:18.910 --> 00:17:21.270
I thought I was Puerto Rican
till I was in fourth grade.

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:22.680
True story.

00:17:22.680 --> 00:17:23.771
True story.

00:17:23.771 --> 00:17:25.770
If somebody asked me, I'm
Boricua, I don't know.

00:17:25.770 --> 00:17:27.186
Then somebody said,
wait a minute,

00:17:27.186 --> 00:17:29.280
your parents are from
the Dominican Republic.

00:17:29.280 --> 00:17:30.660
And then it gets even
funnier, because then

00:17:30.660 --> 00:17:31.690
what do you identify as?

00:17:31.690 --> 00:17:33.390
I'm a black and white Dominican.

00:17:33.390 --> 00:17:34.980
And then as you become more
and more aware, you say,

00:17:34.980 --> 00:17:35.610
I'm a mulatto!

00:17:35.610 --> 00:17:36.960
And then some people
don't like that term,

00:17:36.960 --> 00:17:38.280
but I'm a biracial Dominican.

00:17:38.280 --> 00:17:40.860
And it's a really exciting
time, as I mentioned earlier.

00:17:40.860 --> 00:17:43.410
But what's interesting
about the names

00:17:43.410 --> 00:17:47.250
or how you identify yourself
as is that it matters.

00:17:47.250 --> 00:17:49.740
So when I say to
you, I'm Latino,

00:17:49.740 --> 00:17:51.070
and I pride myself on that.

00:17:51.070 --> 00:17:53.580
And I say to myself, I'm
going to study what this means

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:55.280
and how these people
differ from others,

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:57.529
and what are the contributions
that we've made to this

00:17:57.529 --> 00:18:00.210
country, and how are American
of Latino descent-- like I am--

00:18:00.210 --> 00:18:01.380
how are we interesting?

00:18:01.380 --> 00:18:03.542
What do we contribute
to our society?

00:18:03.542 --> 00:18:05.250
It's important that
people have something

00:18:05.250 --> 00:18:06.375
that they can rally around.

00:18:06.375 --> 00:18:10.110
So I know that I'm in the
minority up here when I say--

00:18:10.110 --> 00:18:12.030
and I hope I don't get
kicked off the panel--

00:18:12.030 --> 00:18:14.340
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: We
want diverse voices here, JP.

00:18:14.340 --> 00:18:16.890
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: When I say
I don't subscribe to Latinx,

00:18:16.890 --> 00:18:18.120
I don't.

00:18:18.120 --> 00:18:19.830
I don't subscribe to it.

00:18:19.830 --> 00:18:22.980
I think that it dilutes the real
matters that we're focusing on.

00:18:22.980 --> 00:18:27.870
| think Latinx is a cover for
the Hispanics in our community

00:18:27.870 --> 00:18:30.060
who have a hard time
accepting the transgender

00:18:30.060 --> 00:18:32.880
community or the non-gender
conforming community.

00:18:32.880 --> 00:18:35.970
I think we have to address the
heart and soul of the matter.

00:18:35.970 --> 00:18:38.010
You have to embrace
these people.

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:40.929
These people have been
hiding for centuries.

00:18:40.929 --> 00:18:41.970
You have to embrace them.

00:18:41.970 --> 00:18:43.800
These people are part
of us, and you're not

00:18:43.800 --> 00:18:45.420
to discriminate
against these people.

00:18:45.420 --> 00:18:47.040
Simply creating
an entire new term

00:18:47.040 --> 00:18:48.610
and throwing "x" at the end--

00:18:48.610 --> 00:18:50.880
which is, by the way,
an Americanized thing.

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:54.150
Throwing it in and now making it
part of Latinx to somehow force

00:18:54.150 --> 00:18:57.300
people to recognize that not
everybody's gender conforming

00:18:57.300 --> 00:18:58.980
I think is disingenuous.

00:18:58.980 --> 00:18:59.629
I really do.

00:18:59.629 --> 00:19:01.170
I think we have to
understand that we

00:19:01.170 --> 00:19:02.795
have to change hearts
and minds and not

00:19:02.795 --> 00:19:04.200
the letters in the word.

00:19:04.200 --> 00:19:06.930
And Latinx, although
means well, I

00:19:06.930 --> 00:19:09.000
think creates
divisions between us--

00:19:09.000 --> 00:19:11.610
Latin Americans in
the United States--

00:19:11.610 --> 00:19:14.700
and our counterparts that
are not in the United States.

00:19:14.700 --> 00:19:18.150
And another issue I think
that is important about labels

00:19:18.150 --> 00:19:20.010
is that there is
strength in numbers.

00:19:20.010 --> 00:19:22.200
Today, we have millions
and millions of Latinos

00:19:22.200 --> 00:19:24.930
that are of every race, and
every color, and every gender,

00:19:24.930 --> 00:19:26.887
and every gender identity.

00:19:26.887 --> 00:19:28.470
That it's important
that you recognize

00:19:28.470 --> 00:19:30.428
why we do that politically,
as it is important.

00:19:30.428 --> 00:19:33.487
Because if all of a sudden
tomorrow Hispanic leaders,

00:19:33.487 --> 00:19:35.070
like many of the
people on this panel,

00:19:35.070 --> 00:19:37.050
decide that we're going
to now call ourselves

00:19:37.050 --> 00:19:39.509
by a specific ethnicity,
there won't be that strength.

00:19:39.509 --> 00:19:41.800
There are only a million or
so Dominicans in the United

00:19:41.800 --> 00:19:44.640
States, but there are millions
and millions and millions

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:46.514
of Latinos in the United States.

00:19:46.514 --> 00:19:48.930
So creating further divisions
among a group that's already

00:19:48.930 --> 00:19:53.340
divided on ethnic lines,
racial lines, religious lines,

00:19:53.340 --> 00:19:57.050
at times, adds to the
issues that we face.

00:19:57.050 --> 00:19:59.700
And including this as a
topic of conversation,

00:19:59.700 --> 00:20:02.970
or making this a focal point,
truly dilutes of the fact

00:20:02.970 --> 00:20:05.910
that 33% of the people in
federal prisons look like me

00:20:05.910 --> 00:20:07.500
and have names like mine.

00:20:07.500 --> 00:20:10.560
It dilutes the fact that 22%
of the people in our country

00:20:10.560 --> 00:20:13.740
are in poverty, and almost
all of them look like me

00:20:13.740 --> 00:20:15.610
and have last names like mine.

00:20:15.610 --> 00:20:17.615
So let's focus on
those issues, instead

00:20:17.615 --> 00:20:21.440
of fancying around the letter x,
which is an Americanized thing,

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:23.150
to the realities of
the issues that we're

00:20:23.150 --> 00:20:25.820
facing in our community.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:28.790
AMERICA FERRERA: I'm not sure
I understood all of that.

00:20:28.790 --> 00:20:31.880
I need to take your
class, so that I can.

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:35.900
But what-- you
know, I think it's--

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:37.680
the thing that makes
us all uncomfortable,

00:20:37.680 --> 00:20:39.860
which is contradiction
and dichotomy.

00:20:39.860 --> 00:20:43.417
And how, yes,
labeling separates us.

00:20:43.417 --> 00:20:45.500
But at the same time, if
you can't name something,

00:20:45.500 --> 00:20:46.370
you can't face it.

00:20:46.370 --> 00:20:48.210
You can't claim it,
you can't deal with it.

00:20:48.210 --> 00:20:50.210
And this is
something that I feel

00:20:50.210 --> 00:20:55.910
like I've been sitting with
and thinking about just

00:20:55.910 --> 00:21:00.200
in the last couple of months
since the election is, how do I

00:21:00.200 --> 00:21:04.310
claim my Latina-ness,
which is not

00:21:04.310 --> 00:21:05.870
separate from my American-ness?

00:21:05.870 --> 00:21:11.240
So as an American, I feel OK
using things that are American,

00:21:11.240 --> 00:21:12.950
like adding x to
the end of a word.

00:21:12.950 --> 00:21:14.817
Because I am fully American.

00:21:14.817 --> 00:21:16.400
I was born and raised
in this country.

00:21:16.400 --> 00:21:18.230
I consider myself an American.

00:21:18.230 --> 00:21:19.790
And that was an
identity that I felt

00:21:19.790 --> 00:21:23.510
stronger connected to way before
I understood my own Latino

00:21:23.510 --> 00:21:24.150
identity.

00:21:24.150 --> 00:21:26.330
So I don't think of
my Latino identity

00:21:26.330 --> 00:21:28.850
as having to be purified
from my American identity

00:21:28.850 --> 00:21:30.980
or separate from.

00:21:30.980 --> 00:21:33.920
But I also-- what
I've been sitting with

00:21:33.920 --> 00:21:38.480
is, how do I claim, and
protect, and make space

00:21:38.480 --> 00:21:45.350
for my Latino identity, but
not let it keep me from all

00:21:45.350 --> 00:21:46.970
my other experiences?

00:21:46.970 --> 00:21:50.180
And I'm most concerned,
in this moment,

00:21:50.180 --> 00:21:55.040
about how we start
widening the circles of how

00:21:55.040 --> 00:21:56.660
we relate to one another.

00:21:56.660 --> 00:21:58.580
You know, is my skin black?

00:21:58.580 --> 00:22:00.850
No, but I relate to
the black experience.

00:22:00.850 --> 00:22:01.610
Am I gay?

00:22:01.610 --> 00:22:02.860
No, but I relate to the gay.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:03.620
Am I trans?

00:22:03.620 --> 00:22:04.915
No, but I relate to that.

00:22:04.915 --> 00:22:06.290
I will stand for
that experience.

00:22:06.290 --> 00:22:07.970
I will stand with those people.

00:22:07.970 --> 00:22:13.730
And my heart is a part of
that battle, that struggle,

00:22:13.730 --> 00:22:15.050
that fight, as well.

00:22:15.050 --> 00:22:24.980
And so it is, to me, a real
uncomfortable conversation

00:22:24.980 --> 00:22:28.070
to have about labels.

00:22:28.070 --> 00:22:32.790
Because, on one hand, until
I could say to myself,

00:22:32.790 --> 00:22:37.720
I'm a Latina, I am--

00:22:37.720 --> 00:22:41.100
and that's going to mean to me
what I decide it means to me.

00:22:41.100 --> 00:22:44.360
And I don't have to go around,
in my particular industry,

00:22:44.360 --> 00:22:46.160
hiding the fact
that I'm Latina so I

00:22:46.160 --> 00:22:48.590
can get this job, that
job, and this job.

00:22:48.590 --> 00:22:52.130
Like being able to say that--
walk into a room, claim that,

00:22:52.130 --> 00:22:55.070
be proud of that, know
that that's what I am,

00:22:55.070 --> 00:22:58.070
and know that it shouldn't
stop me from the opportunity

00:22:58.070 --> 00:23:00.100
and access that I so desire--

00:23:00.100 --> 00:23:01.340
mattered to me.

00:23:01.340 --> 00:23:03.290
And so I do think labels matter.

00:23:03.290 --> 00:23:05.390
And I do think
identifying yourself

00:23:05.390 --> 00:23:12.120
as certain things changes
how you are in the world.

00:23:12.120 --> 00:23:14.870
And I think that there's
the contradiction of,

00:23:14.870 --> 00:23:18.410
yes, there are ways and times
in which it separates us

00:23:18.410 --> 00:23:19.230
from one another.

00:23:19.230 --> 00:23:20.960
So I think it's--

00:23:20.960 --> 00:23:24.950
I think it's more complicated
than just sort of dismissing

00:23:24.950 --> 00:23:27.765
labels as a bad thing.

00:23:27.765 --> 00:23:29.140
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

00:23:29.140 --> 00:23:29.900
Dr. Gonzales?

00:23:29.900 --> 00:23:30.260
RHONDA GONZALEZ: OK.

00:23:30.260 --> 00:23:31.884
So maybe I'm going
to take a little bit

00:23:31.884 --> 00:23:34.260
of a different approach to it.

00:23:34.260 --> 00:23:37.430
So I think-- over time, or
over the course of one's life,

00:23:37.430 --> 00:23:39.287
I think in the United
States, because people

00:23:39.287 --> 00:23:41.120
think about their journey
growing up-- there

00:23:41.120 --> 00:23:44.030
is a tendency, maybe,
say, around youth?

00:23:44.030 --> 00:23:46.370
Maybe from youth to start,
pushing back against labels

00:23:46.370 --> 00:23:48.490
that they grew up with.

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:50.090
Categories they grew up with.

00:23:50.090 --> 00:23:53.960
And I think that's
probably a rite of passage.

00:23:53.960 --> 00:23:57.450
People embrace adolescence,
early adulthood.

00:23:57.450 --> 00:24:00.260
And then they start to see their
worlds become more complicated

00:24:00.260 --> 00:24:05.990
by other identities that are
already [INAUDIBLE] and in use.

00:24:05.990 --> 00:24:08.300
But I think that--

00:24:08.300 --> 00:24:10.820
I have a little bit of a
problem talking about labels.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:12.680
Because what I really
think we're missing

00:24:12.680 --> 00:24:14.510
here is the fact
that we're talking

00:24:14.510 --> 00:24:21.150
about people who are trying
to name their position

00:24:21.150 --> 00:24:24.030
of marginalization in society.

00:24:24.030 --> 00:24:28.470
They're trying to draw attention
to the fact that, in some way,

00:24:28.470 --> 00:24:31.470
their communities are
aggrieved, and that they

00:24:31.470 --> 00:24:36.760
haven't had their foremost
concerns thought about.

00:24:36.760 --> 00:24:40.290
And so whether or not somebody
embraces or pushes back

00:24:40.290 --> 00:24:43.750
against a label I think
comes down to the individual.

00:24:43.750 --> 00:24:46.930
And while I believe everybody's
individuality is important,

00:24:46.930 --> 00:24:49.440
and that's part of an
American kind of sensibility,

00:24:49.440 --> 00:24:51.180
I also think
collectively as a nation

00:24:51.180 --> 00:24:54.180
we need to be thinking
about how these names are

00:24:54.180 --> 00:24:56.010
about a collective ideology.

00:24:56.010 --> 00:24:59.670
The way we are going
to reject, embrace

00:24:59.670 --> 00:25:03.840
our thinking, our
inclusively, our empathy

00:25:03.840 --> 00:25:08.210
for groups that really have
felt that they were on the outs.

00:25:08.210 --> 00:25:11.910
And so-- and I don't think,
as maybe some on this panel

00:25:11.910 --> 00:25:15.000
would argue-- that it's
about just coddling.

00:25:15.000 --> 00:25:16.375
Because this is
serious business,

00:25:16.375 --> 00:25:17.875
you know, the history
of the nation.

00:25:17.875 --> 00:25:19.410
And so if we're
not really thinking

00:25:19.410 --> 00:25:24.060
about how we are proactively
engaging with one another

00:25:24.060 --> 00:25:27.237
and saying, OK,
maybe it's Latinx,

00:25:27.237 --> 00:25:29.070
but what are we really
getting at with that?

00:25:29.070 --> 00:25:33.780
What is undergirding
all of the emotion,

00:25:33.780 --> 00:25:39.300
the structural barriers
and challenges,

00:25:39.300 --> 00:25:43.530
or institutional barriers,
that come with that?

00:25:43.530 --> 00:25:44.115
Right?

00:25:44.115 --> 00:25:45.950
Or that inspire that.

00:25:45.950 --> 00:25:49.830
So I think labels matter.

00:25:49.830 --> 00:25:52.000
But more than that,
I think words matter.

00:25:52.000 --> 00:25:54.090
And so there is a
very real reason

00:25:54.090 --> 00:25:57.240
that words come to
be born for another--

00:25:57.240 --> 00:25:58.800
you know, to use a metaphor.

00:25:58.800 --> 00:25:59.810
There's a very reason.

00:25:59.810 --> 00:26:02.550
And so I think that's what we
really need to think about.

00:26:02.550 --> 00:26:03.966
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Absolutely.

00:26:03.966 --> 00:26:05.630
And thank you so much.

00:26:05.630 --> 00:26:07.170
This is a dialogue
that could go on

00:26:07.170 --> 00:26:10.470
for-- so I'm not going
to completely over invest

00:26:10.470 --> 00:26:11.970
on the labels on the words.

00:26:11.970 --> 00:26:14.850
But I do agree with you,
fundamentally, words do matter.

00:26:14.850 --> 00:26:18.480
And the choice by which we
define ourselves and define

00:26:18.480 --> 00:26:22.410
our place and our context
within this country does matter.

00:26:22.410 --> 00:26:27.390
I'm going to speak a bit now
around the identity category.

00:26:27.390 --> 00:26:28.980
Not just as a
label, but when you

00:26:28.980 --> 00:26:32.560
think about the broader
construct of the Latin American

00:26:32.560 --> 00:26:33.620
community, if you will.

00:26:33.620 --> 00:26:36.880
So that is a group of people
from 26 different countries.

00:26:36.880 --> 00:26:39.110
And different social
class backgrounds,

00:26:39.110 --> 00:26:41.430
different immigrant journeys.

00:26:41.430 --> 00:26:43.650
When data gets
collected on this group,

00:26:43.650 --> 00:26:48.020
as we're discussing right now,
it's discussed as a monolith,

00:26:48.020 --> 00:26:50.640
as a Latin American term.

00:26:50.640 --> 00:26:53.820
What are the risks and
limits to doing so,

00:26:53.820 --> 00:26:55.950
and what could be
alternative approaches

00:26:55.950 --> 00:26:59.947
to highlight range and
variation within the community?

00:26:59.947 --> 00:27:01.280
RHONDA GONZALEZ: May I go first?

00:27:01.280 --> 00:27:01.950
OK.

00:27:01.950 --> 00:27:05.640
Well, I think one of the basic
things that's a little bit

00:27:05.640 --> 00:27:08.520
problematic and challenging for
us is that within those 26--

00:27:08.520 --> 00:27:10.830
and I didn't know
there were 26--

00:27:10.830 --> 00:27:14.080
is that class really matters.

00:27:14.080 --> 00:27:15.510
So what is a starting point?

00:27:15.510 --> 00:27:18.750
You know, for a family,
or individual, or group

00:27:18.750 --> 00:27:22.500
that either has been
here for generations

00:27:22.500 --> 00:27:26.430
or is newly arrived and
is in that category.

00:27:26.430 --> 00:27:29.610
So I think understanding
the class reality

00:27:29.610 --> 00:27:32.460
and how strikingly
different that is,

00:27:32.460 --> 00:27:36.480
and how that also shapes
identity, is really important.

00:27:36.480 --> 00:27:40.140
Also access to social
mobility or economic mobility.

00:27:40.140 --> 00:27:43.440
And I think, you know, as
corporations-- and I mean,

00:27:43.440 --> 00:27:45.840
I'm in an institution
of higher learning.

00:27:45.840 --> 00:27:48.006
So, you know, we
think of ourselves

00:27:48.006 --> 00:27:49.380
a little bit
differently invested

00:27:49.380 --> 00:27:51.930
in the students who
come to our university.

00:27:51.930 --> 00:27:56.550
I think as university leaders,
we need to think about all

00:27:56.550 --> 00:27:57.970
of the heterogeneity
in the room.

00:27:57.970 --> 00:28:00.500
Not just the Latino
heterogeneity--

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:05.310
race, ethnic, religious-- but
also their class diversity.

00:28:05.310 --> 00:28:07.840
Because when you have a group
of people-- in this case,

00:28:07.840 --> 00:28:08.970
students--

00:28:08.970 --> 00:28:12.060
where their ability to
navigate through a system that

00:28:12.060 --> 00:28:15.445
wasn't built for them,
in the case of a Hispanic

00:28:15.445 --> 00:28:17.820
serving institution, which
the University of Texas at San

00:28:17.820 --> 00:28:19.620
Antonio is, you have
a lot of students

00:28:19.620 --> 00:28:20.850
who are arriving there.

00:28:20.850 --> 00:28:22.840
And, for all intents
and purposes,

00:28:22.840 --> 00:28:25.140
the institution is a
middle class environment.

00:28:25.140 --> 00:28:27.202
And many of them arrive
there not middle class.

00:28:27.202 --> 00:28:29.160
I mean, I'm a first
generation college student.

00:28:29.160 --> 00:28:31.960
My mother has a third
grade education.

00:28:31.960 --> 00:28:33.720
My father had an
eighth grade education.

00:28:33.720 --> 00:28:36.954
So when I arrived at UCLA,
I was like, wow, this is--

00:28:36.954 --> 00:28:39.120
and that was my first
experience with Jewish people.

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:41.351
I was like, what is this
salty donut thing they eat?

00:28:41.351 --> 00:28:41.850
You know?

00:28:41.850 --> 00:28:44.220
That's how I thought
about it when I got there.

00:28:44.220 --> 00:28:45.880
You really have a
clash of cultures,

00:28:45.880 --> 00:28:49.620
but also a class clash
of material history

00:28:49.620 --> 00:28:50.700
that often happens.

00:28:50.700 --> 00:28:53.950
And I think that, if we're
not aware of how different--

00:28:53.950 --> 00:28:55.950
and maybe even some of
the employees in the room

00:28:55.950 --> 00:28:57.325
have come from
these backgrounds,

00:28:57.325 --> 00:28:59.280
and then you arrive on
this amazing campus.

00:28:59.280 --> 00:29:02.130
And it's like so state of
the art, and all of this.

00:29:02.130 --> 00:29:05.010
It's like, wow, you know,
I've never really maybe felt

00:29:05.010 --> 00:29:06.750
like I belonged in
this environment.

00:29:06.750 --> 00:29:09.140
And, you know, how am
I going to make sure

00:29:09.140 --> 00:29:11.370
that this is part of my
home so that I can thrive,

00:29:11.370 --> 00:29:13.920
and I can be as
creative and contribute

00:29:13.920 --> 00:29:16.037
as much to this company
as I really want to?

00:29:16.037 --> 00:29:18.120
And so I think the institution
of higher education

00:29:18.120 --> 00:29:19.735
is similar in that way.

00:29:19.735 --> 00:29:21.110
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

00:29:21.110 --> 00:29:22.086
Anyone else?

00:29:22.086 --> 00:29:25.200
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO:
Well, I'll go.

00:29:25.200 --> 00:29:29.060
I hope I was clear,
America and Dr. Gonzalez.

00:29:29.060 --> 00:29:32.162
Labels matter, names
matter, and words matter.

00:29:32.162 --> 00:29:33.370
I thought that was the theme.

00:29:33.370 --> 00:29:36.060
It's just somehow, along
the line, I felt as if--

00:29:36.060 --> 00:29:37.430
I didn't do a lot of debating.

00:29:37.430 --> 00:29:40.010
And I felt as if I was facing
an opponent who countered

00:29:40.010 --> 00:29:41.390
a position that I didn't make.

00:29:41.390 --> 00:29:43.310
So I wanted to make sure that
I was clear with the audience,

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:43.942
as well.

00:29:43.942 --> 00:29:45.650
I'm a firm believer
that names and labels

00:29:45.650 --> 00:29:46.880
and how you identify matter.

00:29:46.880 --> 00:29:48.290
Clearly.

00:29:48.290 --> 00:29:50.587
So this is why this question
is so important as to--

00:29:50.587 --> 00:29:52.920
because we come from all these
different classes and all

00:29:52.920 --> 00:29:56.030
these different races,
how is it that--

00:29:56.030 --> 00:29:58.340
what are some of the
risks that are involved?

00:29:58.340 --> 00:30:02.540
I think there are a lot
of benefits with creating

00:30:02.540 --> 00:30:03.590
a monolithic group.

00:30:03.590 --> 00:30:04.160
There are.

00:30:04.160 --> 00:30:06.200
And let me be very
honest with you guys.

00:30:06.200 --> 00:30:08.390
There is an incredible
amount of benefit.

00:30:08.390 --> 00:30:10.190
When you consider
that politicians

00:30:10.190 --> 00:30:12.850
in this recent election were
talking about the Latino vote,

00:30:12.850 --> 00:30:14.720
as if the Latino
vote was monolithic,

00:30:14.720 --> 00:30:16.900
as if we all just agreed
on the same things,

00:30:16.900 --> 00:30:19.174
and they view us as being
millions and millions

00:30:19.174 --> 00:30:21.340
of people, then they're
going to cater to what is it

00:30:21.340 --> 00:30:23.300
that the Latino people want?

00:30:23.300 --> 00:30:24.950
You can't really quantify that.

00:30:24.950 --> 00:30:27.200
You can't really quantify--
even at Google, what is it

00:30:27.200 --> 00:30:28.550
that the Latino employees want?

00:30:28.550 --> 00:30:29.960
That's a ridiculous question.

00:30:29.960 --> 00:30:31.670
Because the Latino
employees are just

00:30:31.670 --> 00:30:34.490
as diverse as the
non-Latino employees.

00:30:34.490 --> 00:30:37.370
You know, us-- when I say
descendant of Latin America,

00:30:37.370 --> 00:30:39.346
I'm talking about, our
parents are from there,

00:30:39.346 --> 00:30:40.220
and we are Americans.

00:30:40.220 --> 00:30:43.050
Because I claim American, and
it upsets a lot of people,

00:30:43.050 --> 00:30:44.140
especially in New York.

00:30:44.140 --> 00:30:45.530
Because when people come
up to me and ask me,

00:30:45.530 --> 00:30:46.490
where are you from?

00:30:46.490 --> 00:30:48.865
And I go, the Bronx, they're
like, no, no, no, seriously,

00:30:48.865 --> 00:30:49.680
where are you from?

00:30:49.680 --> 00:30:51.200
They want to know more
and more whether-- they

00:30:51.200 --> 00:30:52.430
don't go to the white
guy and ask him that.

00:30:52.430 --> 00:30:53.670
Because the white guy
gets around and says,

00:30:53.670 --> 00:30:56.210
oh, I'm a quarter Italian,
quarter Irish, quarter German.

00:30:56.210 --> 00:30:57.334
And by then, I'm just lost.

00:30:57.334 --> 00:31:00.620
I don't even know how you divide
a human being in quarters.

00:31:00.620 --> 00:31:02.942
So this idea is to--
the benefits that

00:31:02.942 --> 00:31:04.900
are surrounded by just
calling us all Hispanic,

00:31:04.900 --> 00:31:06.590
I think that there are a lot.

00:31:06.590 --> 00:31:09.650
I think that we can take
advantage of that, politically.

00:31:09.650 --> 00:31:11.647
Because politicians
in Washington

00:31:11.647 --> 00:31:12.980
will have to think about things.

00:31:12.980 --> 00:31:13.850
And I hope they do.

00:31:13.850 --> 00:31:16.100
I know they're not right
now, and it really upsets me.

00:31:16.100 --> 00:31:17.750
I hope they realize
that there are

00:31:17.750 --> 00:31:19.760
issues that affect
all of us, regardless

00:31:19.760 --> 00:31:21.170
of our ethnic background.

00:31:21.170 --> 00:31:24.410
There are some issues
like immigration

00:31:24.410 --> 00:31:26.552
that affect us as Latinos.

00:31:26.552 --> 00:31:28.260
You may not be an
undocumented immigrant.

00:31:28.260 --> 00:31:29.780
Your father may not
even be an immigrant.

00:31:29.780 --> 00:31:32.030
You may be here for hundreds
of years, like the person

00:31:32.030 --> 00:31:34.100
that I met earlier today.

00:31:34.100 --> 00:31:38.004
But there are so many
differences between us

00:31:38.004 --> 00:31:39.920
that it's very interesting
to see, how can you

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:41.600
unite all these people?

00:31:41.600 --> 00:31:42.980
And when you say
Latinos, we have

00:31:42.980 --> 00:31:45.650
something in common where
we could identify with.

00:31:45.650 --> 00:31:48.674
And for the most part, we
have Spanish as a language

00:31:48.674 --> 00:31:50.090
that many of us
can identify with.

00:31:50.090 --> 00:31:53.180
And not that all of us
Latinos speak Spanish.

00:31:53.180 --> 00:31:55.059
My kids don't.

00:31:55.059 --> 00:31:57.350
But for the most part, we
have language that unites us,

00:31:57.350 --> 00:31:59.570
and we also have a certain
immigration experience.

00:31:59.570 --> 00:32:02.340
It may be now or it may have
been a couple of years ago.

00:32:02.340 --> 00:32:04.730
And unlike so many of the
Chicanos, and you see labels

00:32:04.730 --> 00:32:05.959
are important, right?

00:32:05.959 --> 00:32:08.250
The Chicanos who have been
here for thousands of years,

00:32:08.250 --> 00:32:10.880
in our territory here
in the United States.

00:32:10.880 --> 00:32:12.910
So labels can matter now.

00:32:12.910 --> 00:32:17.180
And how you identify Latinos
matters for purposes of power.

00:32:17.180 --> 00:32:19.760
And if Hispanics,
or Latinos, begin

00:32:19.760 --> 00:32:21.650
to understand the
importance of how there

00:32:21.650 --> 00:32:24.182
are singular issues that
impact all of us, then

00:32:24.182 --> 00:32:26.390
perhaps we'd be able to get
more power in Washington.

00:32:26.390 --> 00:32:28.400
Perhaps President
Trump would think twice

00:32:28.400 --> 00:32:29.990
before saying some
of the things,

00:32:29.990 --> 00:32:32.180
and how he says some of
the things, about people

00:32:32.180 --> 00:32:33.009
that affect us.

00:32:33.009 --> 00:32:33.800
I'll tell you this.

00:32:33.800 --> 00:32:36.320
On June 16th, 2015--

00:32:36.320 --> 00:32:38.720
as a Republican, and
this was very hard--

00:32:38.720 --> 00:32:40.790
I became a never
Trump Republican.

00:32:40.790 --> 00:32:43.730
Because Donald Trump came down
those escalators and blasted

00:32:43.730 --> 00:32:45.120
undocumented immigrants.

00:32:45.120 --> 00:32:47.150
Blasted Mexicans, in particular.

00:32:47.150 --> 00:32:48.770
Now I'm not Mexican.

00:32:48.770 --> 00:32:51.380
I know a couple of Mexicans
in New York, but I'm not.

00:32:51.380 --> 00:32:54.530
But when he did that,
I felt insulted.

00:32:54.530 --> 00:32:57.110
I felt like, my people
just got dissed!

00:32:57.110 --> 00:32:58.820
On TV!

00:32:58.820 --> 00:33:01.470
We're murderers, and rapists,
and we're not the best?

00:33:01.470 --> 00:33:03.140
And it bothered me,
but I had nothing--

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:05.030
if you look down
my ancestry DNA,

00:33:05.030 --> 00:33:06.980
you're going to find
Mexican anywhere.

00:33:06.980 --> 00:33:09.067
But I felt an affinity.

00:33:09.067 --> 00:33:09.650
I felt a bond.

00:33:09.650 --> 00:33:11.460
I felt an allegiance
to these people.

00:33:11.460 --> 00:33:13.560
So there are some very
good things that happened.

00:33:13.560 --> 00:33:15.230
And I was very angry about that.

00:33:15.230 --> 00:33:17.180
Because, when he
did that, he really

00:33:17.180 --> 00:33:19.310
castigated an entire
group of people.

00:33:19.310 --> 00:33:21.060
When he did that about
the Mexican people,

00:33:21.060 --> 00:33:22.835
I knew that he was
thinking about me.

00:33:22.835 --> 00:33:23.960
AMERICA FERRERA: Of course.

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:24.950
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO:
I knew that.

00:33:24.950 --> 00:33:25.736
I knew he was thinking
about me, and he

00:33:25.736 --> 00:33:26.840
was thinking about us up here.

00:33:26.840 --> 00:33:27.880
AMERICA FERRERA: He doesn't
know the difference--

00:33:27.880 --> 00:33:29.046
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: I know.

00:33:29.046 --> 00:33:31.200
I know he was, and
it bothers me, a lot.

00:33:31.200 --> 00:33:31.820
A lot.

00:33:31.820 --> 00:33:34.190
And I wish I could talk to him,
but because I was never Trump,

00:33:34.190 --> 00:33:35.523
I'm not allowed near Washington.

00:33:35.523 --> 00:33:36.890
[LAUGHTER]

00:33:36.890 --> 00:33:38.840
Anywhere near it.

00:33:38.840 --> 00:33:41.360
But there are some advantages
for knowing the differences,

00:33:41.360 --> 00:33:43.010
and this is why I get excited.

00:33:43.010 --> 00:33:46.220
Once you realize that the Latin
American experience is very

00:33:46.220 --> 00:33:49.130
similar to the so-called
American experience,

00:33:49.130 --> 00:33:50.190
and that our history--

00:33:50.190 --> 00:33:51.950
and I know Dr. Gonzalez
as a historian.

00:33:51.950 --> 00:33:53.300
She'd appreciate this.

00:33:53.300 --> 00:33:54.780
Our history is very similar.

00:33:54.780 --> 00:33:56.120
It is.

00:33:56.120 --> 00:33:58.730
We had a slave experience
in the United States.

00:33:58.730 --> 00:34:00.950
We had a slave experience
in Latin America.

00:34:00.950 --> 00:34:03.946
We had a European
conquest in North America.

00:34:03.946 --> 00:34:05.570
We had the same thing
in South America.

00:34:05.570 --> 00:34:07.670
We have a class structure
based on race in North

00:34:07.670 --> 00:34:08.760
America for the most part.

00:34:08.760 --> 00:34:10.219
Not always, but
it just so happens

00:34:10.219 --> 00:34:12.260
to be that the wealthiest
are of a certain class,

00:34:12.260 --> 00:34:13.100
of a certain race.

00:34:13.100 --> 00:34:14.933
And then you go to Latin
America, especially

00:34:14.933 --> 00:34:16.540
in the Caribbean, very similar.

00:34:16.540 --> 00:34:18.590
The percentage of
the class elites,

00:34:18.590 --> 00:34:20.100
or all of the
European descendancy,

00:34:20.100 --> 00:34:23.062
and the great majority of the
people in poverty, are not.

00:34:23.062 --> 00:34:24.520
So there are a lot
of similarities.

00:34:24.520 --> 00:34:27.900
And I think once it becomes more
common for non-Latino students

00:34:27.900 --> 00:34:29.400
to enroll in Latino
studies classes,

00:34:29.400 --> 00:34:30.500
and to learn about
what Dominicans are,

00:34:30.500 --> 00:34:31.800
and Puerto Ricans
are, and Mexicans

00:34:31.800 --> 00:34:34.008
are, and know how important
the Mexican community has

00:34:34.008 --> 00:34:36.570
been in the United States--
how 63% of our population that

00:34:36.570 --> 00:34:37.529
is Hispanic is Mexican.

00:34:37.529 --> 00:34:39.278
When you study the
contributions that they

00:34:39.278 --> 00:34:40.409
made to civil rights--

00:34:40.409 --> 00:34:43.080
although not as covered as the
African-American civil rights

00:34:43.080 --> 00:34:45.719
movements, and I understand
the frustration for some--

00:34:45.719 --> 00:34:47.940
you'd appreciate, have
a sense of appreciation.

00:34:47.940 --> 00:34:50.219
And that's I continue to
say, if our politicians,

00:34:50.219 --> 00:34:52.949
and our leaders take an
opportunity just read a book,

00:34:52.949 --> 00:34:55.120
or have a discussion with
one of our panelists,

00:34:55.120 --> 00:34:56.639
they'd think twice before
saying some of the things

00:34:56.639 --> 00:34:58.020
that they've done and said.

00:34:58.020 --> 00:34:59.186
And I'll say one more thing.

00:34:59.186 --> 00:35:01.430
America, I'm sorry that
I'm taking so much time.

00:35:01.430 --> 00:35:03.600
And I hate to beat
up on my own guys.

00:35:03.600 --> 00:35:05.760
But Senator Sessions on
the floor of the US Senate

00:35:05.760 --> 00:35:07.800
in 2006--

00:35:07.800 --> 00:35:10.740
not in some club,
not during lunch,

00:35:10.740 --> 00:35:15.210
on the floor in 2006 said
that-- and I'm paraphrasing--

00:35:15.210 --> 00:35:17.160
that immigrants from
the Dominican Republic

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:18.659
have nothing to
offer our economy.

00:35:18.659 --> 00:35:20.700
Because of that, they have
nothing to contribute.

00:35:20.700 --> 00:35:22.270
It broke my heart.

00:35:22.270 --> 00:35:23.550
It devastated me.

00:35:23.550 --> 00:35:24.942
I said, well, how can that be?

00:35:24.942 --> 00:35:26.400
How could it be
that the only thing

00:35:26.400 --> 00:35:27.983
they identify with
Dominican-Americans

00:35:27.983 --> 00:35:29.110
is baseball?

00:35:29.110 --> 00:35:32.185
How don't they know about
Junot Diaz or Julia Alvarez?

00:35:32.185 --> 00:35:34.560
Do they not understand the
contributions that we've made?

00:35:34.560 --> 00:35:36.120
Or even Oscar de La Renta?

00:35:36.120 --> 00:35:38.850
You can go down the list
and study how that's

00:35:38.850 --> 00:35:40.260
an awful statement to make.

00:35:40.260 --> 00:35:43.914
That man today is the attorney
general of the United States.

00:35:43.914 --> 00:35:45.330
And I blame the
fact that we don't

00:35:45.330 --> 00:35:46.934
talk enough about
our contributions

00:35:46.934 --> 00:35:49.350
to the United States, and we
don't hold people to account.

00:35:49.350 --> 00:35:50.430
To learn about our struggle.

00:35:50.430 --> 00:35:52.470
To learn about what we've
done, what we've overcome,

00:35:52.470 --> 00:35:53.678
and what we have contributed.

00:35:53.678 --> 00:35:54.670
So I think they--

00:35:54.670 --> 00:35:55.810
I know I spoke too long.

00:35:55.810 --> 00:35:56.370
I'm sorry, America.

00:35:56.370 --> 00:35:58.120
But I think it's
important that I'm clear.

00:35:58.120 --> 00:35:59.910
Because when I'm
not clear, I panic.

00:35:59.910 --> 00:36:01.493
So I want to make
sure that I'm clear.

00:36:01.493 --> 00:36:02.610
[LAUGHTER]

00:36:02.610 --> 00:36:03.970
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: We're
going to avoid you panicking,

00:36:03.970 --> 00:36:06.110
JC, but are going to
move over to America now.

00:36:06.110 --> 00:36:07.280
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: When
I heard America tackle me,

00:36:07.280 --> 00:36:09.510
I said, America, you're
beating me up for no reason!

00:36:09.510 --> 00:36:10.801
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: America?

00:36:10.801 --> 00:36:12.410
AMERICA FERRERA: I'm passionate!

00:36:12.410 --> 00:36:14.160
I'm-- am I allowed to say this?

00:36:14.160 --> 00:36:15.360
I'm Latina!

00:36:15.360 --> 00:36:16.209
Yes.

00:36:16.209 --> 00:36:17.000
What do you expect?

00:36:17.000 --> 00:36:18.640
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:36:18.640 --> 00:36:21.780
AMERICA FERRERA: That's a
stereotype I get to use, right?

00:36:21.780 --> 00:36:22.990
Own it.

00:36:22.990 --> 00:36:25.500
This is something
that we are constantly

00:36:25.500 --> 00:36:29.070
talking about inside of
the entertainment industry.

00:36:29.070 --> 00:36:30.672
Because everybody
wants to know, how

00:36:30.672 --> 00:36:31.880
do you get the Latino market?

00:36:31.880 --> 00:36:33.580
How do you get
the Latino market?

00:36:33.580 --> 00:36:39.030
And there's so much nuance
lost in that mindset.

00:36:39.030 --> 00:36:43.170
You know, I think there's an
importance differentiating

00:36:43.170 --> 00:36:46.060
diversity of race and
diversity of experience.

00:36:46.060 --> 00:36:49.470
And, you know-- and
both have value.

00:36:49.470 --> 00:36:56.970
And if a Latino, any Latino,
is dehumanized and ridiculed

00:36:56.970 --> 00:37:00.660
by anyone, much less someone
running for president,

00:37:00.660 --> 00:37:02.370
it hurts us all.

00:37:02.370 --> 00:37:05.510
And if a Latino succeeds,
we all claim it.

00:37:05.510 --> 00:37:10.020
We take the pride in
that, because we do.

00:37:10.020 --> 00:37:13.320
However, that doesn't
mean that, if there's

00:37:13.320 --> 00:37:16.260
a Latino at the head
of said studio, that's

00:37:16.260 --> 00:37:20.190
going to translate to my
experience as a Latino

00:37:20.190 --> 00:37:22.650
in their stories and
the stories they tell.

00:37:22.650 --> 00:37:28.110
And so, you know, I have
tried from before I ever even

00:37:28.110 --> 00:37:33.060
imagined myself a producer,
a 17-year-old kid trying

00:37:33.060 --> 00:37:36.400
to talk to a film
studio about like,

00:37:36.400 --> 00:37:38.670
don't market to
Latinos that way.

00:37:38.670 --> 00:37:41.010
Because who you're
talking to is me,

00:37:41.010 --> 00:37:43.890
and I grew up watching "Fresh
Prince of Bel Air" and "Family

00:37:43.890 --> 00:37:45.610
Matters" and "Dawson's Creek."

00:37:45.610 --> 00:37:50.940
And if you're looking for me,
then maybe listen a little bit

00:37:50.940 --> 00:37:54.210
to the nuance of what
someone like me wants.

00:37:54.210 --> 00:37:57.750
I want to see people who look
like me in all these stories,

00:37:57.750 --> 00:37:59.790
in all these images.

00:37:59.790 --> 00:38:01.770
But that doesn't
necessarily mean

00:38:01.770 --> 00:38:06.030
that if you just throw the word
"telenovela" in it, I'm like,

00:38:06.030 --> 00:38:06.960
that's me!

00:38:06.960 --> 00:38:09.660
You know, that's-- I walked
out of the room if my mom put

00:38:09.660 --> 00:38:10.380
on a telenovela.

00:38:10.380 --> 00:38:11.670
I couldn't stand it.

00:38:11.670 --> 00:38:13.633
Or, you know, if it's
just half in Spanish,

00:38:13.633 --> 00:38:16.091
it's all of a sudden going to
appeal to all of the Latinos.

00:38:19.550 --> 00:38:22.170
It will never
equal good business

00:38:22.170 --> 00:38:24.570
to think of us as a monolith.

00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:28.050
And that's why I think
that this term of Latinx--

00:38:28.050 --> 00:38:32.460
which I think I may not
even understand fully,

00:38:32.460 --> 00:38:35.700
so I would love kind
of a concise definition

00:38:35.700 --> 00:38:38.850
of what Latinx means--

00:38:38.850 --> 00:38:42.450
it has-- even as a producer,
even as a storyteller,

00:38:42.450 --> 00:38:46.620
even as somebody who goes out
on a daily basis and speaks

00:38:46.620 --> 00:38:53.430
to content makers about this
young group of Latinos who

00:38:53.430 --> 00:38:57.420
identify themselves as not
the Latino that you have

00:38:57.420 --> 00:38:58.770
in your mind--

00:38:58.770 --> 00:39:05.580
it's given us agency and power
to delineate ourselves inside

00:39:05.580 --> 00:39:07.189
of that monolith.

00:39:07.189 --> 00:39:08.730
And there's power
in that when you're

00:39:08.730 --> 00:39:11.730
having conversations about
storytelling and business

00:39:11.730 --> 00:39:16.220
and nuance inside of a very,
very, very broad stroke.

00:39:16.220 --> 00:39:20.130
That doesn't serve us when--

00:39:20.130 --> 00:39:23.490
if you're a politician,
or if you're a businessman

00:39:23.490 --> 00:39:27.670
genuinely trying to reach
a specific audience.

00:39:27.670 --> 00:39:33.380
Because our experiences are so
vastly nuanced and different.

00:39:33.380 --> 00:39:34.755
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Andrew, do

00:39:34.755 --> 00:39:36.171
you want to speak
about continuing

00:39:36.171 --> 00:39:38.875
to embrace our nuances?

00:39:38.875 --> 00:39:39.750
ANDREW HERRERA: Yeah.

00:39:39.750 --> 00:39:42.450
I think there's one uniform
theme for all of us,

00:39:42.450 --> 00:39:44.790
is that I think we're proud.

00:39:44.790 --> 00:39:48.420
We're very proud of what
this culture represents.

00:39:48.420 --> 00:39:50.550
I think we all have
different definitions

00:39:50.550 --> 00:39:54.600
or have different experiences
on how that plays out.

00:39:54.600 --> 00:39:59.670
And I think, for me
personally, I think, you know,

00:39:59.670 --> 00:40:02.490
what I've created
was-- you know,

00:40:02.490 --> 00:40:07.230
I created a forum that was out
of an identity crisis of me

00:40:07.230 --> 00:40:12.120
wanting to not really
identify as a Latino.

00:40:12.120 --> 00:40:15.120
And, you know, I
was born Andres,

00:40:15.120 --> 00:40:16.360
and my name is Andrew today.

00:40:16.360 --> 00:40:16.860
Why?

00:40:16.860 --> 00:40:20.190
Because, in the 90s,
my name was "undress"

00:40:20.190 --> 00:40:24.210
or "Andre as," and no one
knew how to-- and that was--

00:40:24.210 --> 00:40:27.810
but today, Andres is cool.

00:40:27.810 --> 00:40:30.600
And where I'm going with
this is that I think--

00:40:30.600 --> 00:40:33.450
in today's environment,
I think I'm

00:40:33.450 --> 00:40:37.980
starting to see more pride
than I've ever seen before.

00:40:37.980 --> 00:40:40.920
And that didn't necessarily
come through labels.

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:44.520
I think that came
through the culture

00:40:44.520 --> 00:40:47.160
evolving and the
influence that we've

00:40:47.160 --> 00:40:50.070
had beyond our own
community, right?

00:40:50.070 --> 00:40:55.290
Beyond kind of just
Hispanics, but how we see--

00:40:55.290 --> 00:40:59.820
I think our non-Hispanic
friends embrace our own culture,

00:40:59.820 --> 00:41:03.450
and I think that allows
us to also go down

00:41:03.450 --> 00:41:07.350
this new path of having
an identity that, one, we

00:41:07.350 --> 00:41:08.940
can be proud about.

00:41:08.940 --> 00:41:13.240
Two, can continue to evolve.

00:41:13.240 --> 00:41:15.540
And that isn't only
based off of race.

00:41:15.540 --> 00:41:20.070
I mean, I-- you know,
it's pretty frustrating.

00:41:20.070 --> 00:41:22.836
You know, one of
the reasons I do

00:41:22.836 --> 00:41:24.210
what I do and I
love what I do is

00:41:24.210 --> 00:41:26.760
because I get to
break stereotypes even

00:41:26.760 --> 00:41:28.980
within my own community.

00:41:28.980 --> 00:41:30.990
You know, for example, it's--

00:41:30.990 --> 00:41:32.430
we talk about Afro-Latinos.

00:41:32.430 --> 00:41:34.360
And it's something that
we talk about today,

00:41:34.360 --> 00:41:38.190
but Afro-Latinos have been
part of the Hispanic community,

00:41:38.190 --> 00:41:41.490
Latin community, Latinx
community for decades.

00:41:41.490 --> 00:41:43.890
But you never saw
them on Univision.

00:41:43.890 --> 00:41:45.810
You never saw them on Telemundo.

00:41:45.810 --> 00:41:47.430
They were never
a representation.

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:52.920
I know a lot of friends that I
didn't even know were Latino.

00:41:52.920 --> 00:41:58.410
That were basically assimilated
to African-American-- you know,

00:41:58.410 --> 00:42:01.190
being--

00:42:01.190 --> 00:42:03.570
calling themselves
African-American without

00:42:03.570 --> 00:42:07.947
mentioning that they were
Latino, because that wasn't--

00:42:07.947 --> 00:42:09.030
they didn't feel welcomed.

00:42:09.030 --> 00:42:11.810
So I think-- but
today, we're starting

00:42:11.810 --> 00:42:16.410
to see that evolve into
where they are welcomed,

00:42:16.410 --> 00:42:18.579
or that we talk
about these issues

00:42:18.579 --> 00:42:19.620
within our own community.

00:42:19.620 --> 00:42:23.110
So I agree with some of what
you're saying, but I also--

00:42:23.110 --> 00:42:25.860
but I disagree in
terms of it just

00:42:25.860 --> 00:42:27.960
being about a label
that we get behind.

00:42:27.960 --> 00:42:34.200
I think what we get behind
is that we are influencing

00:42:34.200 --> 00:42:36.960
and that we want to
push others to be

00:42:36.960 --> 00:42:40.680
more fluent in our culture, not
just in how people define us.

00:42:40.680 --> 00:42:43.530
And I think if we
do that well, I

00:42:43.530 --> 00:42:47.430
think this conversation goes
from actually not just being

00:42:47.430 --> 00:42:50.430
an academic conversation
but a conversation that

00:42:50.430 --> 00:42:53.040
goes into practice in terms
of how people make decisions.

00:42:53.040 --> 00:42:56.654
Whether it be around
content, around--

00:42:56.654 --> 00:42:58.820
you know, around-- I deal
with a lot of advertisers,

00:42:58.820 --> 00:43:02.430
and it's like being
in the dark ages

00:43:02.430 --> 00:43:08.670
sometimes about how they
want to chase and really

00:43:08.670 --> 00:43:10.830
communicate with our community.

00:43:10.830 --> 00:43:13.110
So I do hope that--

00:43:13.110 --> 00:43:16.470
I think we do need
to embrace this time,

00:43:16.470 --> 00:43:19.680
and I think the fact
today is that we

00:43:19.680 --> 00:43:21.540
do have this great pride.

00:43:21.540 --> 00:43:23.340
We do have this great diversity.

00:43:23.340 --> 00:43:24.820
But I think we're
just beginning.

00:43:24.820 --> 00:43:28.500
And I think we have to
embrace something like Latinx,

00:43:28.500 --> 00:43:32.490
but embrace it for the people
that it means something for,

00:43:32.490 --> 00:43:37.500
not put it as a label that a
group has to identify with.

00:43:37.500 --> 00:43:39.249
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
I'm going to switch

00:43:39.249 --> 00:43:40.590
slightly away from the label.

00:43:40.590 --> 00:43:44.100
I know we keep on revisiting it,
but it is such a salient topic,

00:43:44.100 --> 00:43:47.460
and something that we do need
to discuss amongst ourselves,

00:43:47.460 --> 00:43:50.130
and also for the
wonderful audience that's

00:43:50.130 --> 00:43:51.780
watching us today.

00:43:51.780 --> 00:43:56.280
But I want to pick up on
your comment around race

00:43:56.280 --> 00:43:58.290
within the Latino community.

00:43:58.290 --> 00:44:01.650
And we're not comfortable
talking about race

00:44:01.650 --> 00:44:03.000
within the Latino community.

00:44:03.000 --> 00:44:04.950
Racial hierarchy,
white privilege

00:44:04.950 --> 00:44:06.420
within the Latino community.

00:44:06.420 --> 00:44:09.110
And I'd love to hear
from all of you,

00:44:09.110 --> 00:44:12.150
or if anyone in particular
who wants to speak about,

00:44:12.150 --> 00:44:13.950
how does that show up for us?

00:44:13.950 --> 00:44:17.550
And how has it shown up,
if at all, for any of you

00:44:17.550 --> 00:44:19.770
individually?

00:44:19.770 --> 00:44:22.100
AMERICA FERRERA: Well,
I think I started my--

00:44:22.100 --> 00:44:23.700
the first thing I
said was very much

00:44:23.700 --> 00:44:29.010
based on learning
what kind of Latino

00:44:29.010 --> 00:44:31.710
was an OK Latino to be when
you were growing up in the San

00:44:31.710 --> 00:44:33.578
Fernando Valley and seeing--

00:44:37.242 --> 00:44:42.570
you know, seeing the
version of Latino that

00:44:42.570 --> 00:44:45.900
was sort of dismissed
and stereotyped and put

00:44:45.900 --> 00:44:49.440
in a certain box,
and not wanting

00:44:49.440 --> 00:44:50.690
to be shoved in that box.

00:44:50.690 --> 00:44:53.810
Therefore, trying to make
myself as different as possible.

00:44:53.810 --> 00:44:55.140
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: Was
that because of socioeconomics

00:44:55.140 --> 00:44:55.710
or because of race?

00:44:55.710 --> 00:44:57.918
AMERICA FERRERA: I think it
was about a lot of stuff.

00:44:57.918 --> 00:45:01.710
I think, for one, I think
race is a really, really

00:45:01.710 --> 00:45:02.480
big part of that.

00:45:02.480 --> 00:45:04.320
I think that-- I heard
a friend say this,

00:45:04.320 --> 00:45:05.760
and it seems so true to me.

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:11.100
When people demonize or
don't like your Latino-ness,

00:45:11.100 --> 00:45:13.860
it's not the European
part of your Latino-ness

00:45:13.860 --> 00:45:15.270
they don't like.

00:45:15.270 --> 00:45:17.070
It's the brown part.

00:45:17.070 --> 00:45:19.370
It's the indigenous part.

00:45:19.370 --> 00:45:22.320
And, I mean, I saw
a horrible example

00:45:22.320 --> 00:45:25.080
of that on social media.

00:45:25.080 --> 00:45:27.060
There was all kinds of
horrible things being

00:45:27.060 --> 00:45:30.270
said during the Super Bowl,
and someone was talking about

00:45:30.270 --> 00:45:33.430
like Gisele Bundchen being
Brazilian and people saying,

00:45:33.430 --> 00:45:34.650
yeah, but she's white.

00:45:34.650 --> 00:45:35.850
She's a white Brazilian.

00:45:35.850 --> 00:45:38.610
And that's not Latino,
and therefore white people

00:45:38.610 --> 00:45:40.520
are still supreme.

00:45:40.520 --> 00:45:43.620
And that sort of stuff,
it's such a key reminder

00:45:43.620 --> 00:45:45.870
of what we don't like to
discuss and talk about.

00:45:45.870 --> 00:45:49.680
Which is-- is that race
plays such a huge part.

00:45:49.680 --> 00:45:51.510
And, you know, I'll say it.

00:45:51.510 --> 00:45:54.000
Like the older family
members I grew up

00:45:54.000 --> 00:45:58.690
with spoke of black people
in the most demeaning ways.

00:45:58.690 --> 00:45:59.190
You know?

00:45:59.190 --> 00:46:02.450
Race was always a part
of the conversation.

00:46:02.450 --> 00:46:05.587
And I remember--
I won't say who,

00:46:05.587 --> 00:46:07.170
because I feel like
they'd be ashamed.

00:46:07.170 --> 00:46:10.710
But an older person in
my family would always

00:46:10.710 --> 00:46:13.962
say to my half white,
half Latina cousin,

00:46:13.962 --> 00:46:15.420
come out of the
sun or you're going

00:46:15.420 --> 00:46:16.628
to be dark like your cousins.

00:46:17.280 --> 00:46:21.210
Or my mother would never ever
let me go out into the sun

00:46:21.210 --> 00:46:23.950
without sunscreen, and a
hat, and, come out of there,

00:46:23.950 --> 00:46:25.470
you don't want to look like--

00:46:25.470 --> 00:46:29.730
you know, a campesina
or whatever.

00:46:29.730 --> 00:46:35.280
We grew up with that constant
sort of injection of race

00:46:35.280 --> 00:46:40.400
always, and skin color
being a part of a hierarchy.

00:46:40.400 --> 00:46:43.340
And you wanted to be a
light skinned Latino.

00:46:43.340 --> 00:46:45.320
You didn't want
to have an accent.

00:46:45.320 --> 00:46:48.690
I mean, we grew up not
even speaking Spanish.

00:46:48.690 --> 00:46:53.190
Because to speak
Spanish, I believe--

00:46:53.190 --> 00:46:56.250
assuming the best of
my parents, they just

00:46:56.250 --> 00:46:57.930
wanted the best for us.

00:46:57.930 --> 00:47:02.370
So it was about
wanting to be perceived

00:47:02.370 --> 00:47:05.010
as someone who could
take advantage of all

00:47:05.010 --> 00:47:06.970
the opportunities and succeed.

00:47:06.970 --> 00:47:12.090
And so much of that was
about stripping away

00:47:12.090 --> 00:47:14.370
the parts of being Latino
that other people weren't

00:47:14.370 --> 00:47:15.790
comfortable with.

00:47:15.790 --> 00:47:17.490
And it was about other.

00:47:17.490 --> 00:47:18.980
It was about be as much--

00:47:18.980 --> 00:47:20.580
try to be as much
of a white person

00:47:20.580 --> 00:47:24.390
as you can in America to
be a successful Latino.

00:47:24.390 --> 00:47:27.630
And I've had to
reckon with that,

00:47:27.630 --> 00:47:31.950
and think about how that
has shaped who I am,

00:47:31.950 --> 00:47:39.690
and go on this journey of
learning that my value is

00:47:39.690 --> 00:47:46.200
inherently there and not based
upon, you know, how appealing I

00:47:46.200 --> 00:47:48.305
am to the people
in powerful rooms.

00:47:48.305 --> 00:47:49.680
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

00:47:49.680 --> 00:47:51.013
[INAUDIBLE], would you like to--

00:47:51.013 --> 00:47:52.682
RHONDA GONZALEZ: Sure.

00:47:52.682 --> 00:47:54.390
Well, I guess I'm one
of those people who

00:47:54.390 --> 00:47:56.860
is not uncomfortable
talking about race at all.

00:47:56.860 --> 00:48:00.180
But I do think that--

00:48:00.180 --> 00:48:02.340
again, I think nuance of
language is important.

00:48:02.340 --> 00:48:05.382
And I think we all need to
be reminded again and again

00:48:05.382 --> 00:48:06.840
that when we're
talking about race,

00:48:06.840 --> 00:48:09.240
we're talking about
large systems of power,

00:48:09.240 --> 00:48:13.130
and not just individual
prejudices or biases,

00:48:13.130 --> 00:48:15.460
and those kinds of things.

00:48:15.460 --> 00:48:19.350
But I do think that there is
a deep historical and colonial

00:48:19.350 --> 00:48:21.164
legacy that is part--

00:48:21.164 --> 00:48:22.080
been referred to here.

00:48:22.080 --> 00:48:26.130
And that is the
roots of Latinidad

00:48:26.130 --> 00:48:32.010
is inclusive of Africans,
indigenous folks, and then

00:48:32.010 --> 00:48:33.750
all kinds of Iberian people.

00:48:33.750 --> 00:48:36.240
Really complicated as well
from the Iberian world.

00:48:36.240 --> 00:48:38.640
And those colonial
legacies, in part,

00:48:38.640 --> 00:48:43.680
JC mentioned, you see in access
to material wealth still today.

00:48:43.680 --> 00:48:45.180
And those are like
the legacies we

00:48:45.180 --> 00:48:47.790
see in especially Latin
American countries, when we're

00:48:47.790 --> 00:48:51.300
talking about Latino nations.

00:48:51.300 --> 00:48:53.320
And so there's that.

00:48:53.320 --> 00:48:55.560
But I also think the
uncomfortable part is not

00:48:55.560 --> 00:49:00.350
so much race as it is
the color discrimination,

00:49:00.350 --> 00:49:03.930
or which is now, in the
literature, an evolving

00:49:03.930 --> 00:49:05.790
field of colorism.

00:49:05.790 --> 00:49:08.760
And that is-- and I won't
mention names either,

00:49:08.760 --> 00:49:11.490
but the first time I went back
to East Texas-- my parents

00:49:11.490 --> 00:49:14.280
migrated here in 1954.

00:49:14.280 --> 00:49:17.160
And then, college graduation,
I had this really great idea.

00:49:17.160 --> 00:49:19.810
I want to go see where I came,
where my parents came from.

00:49:19.810 --> 00:49:21.530
And so took Mom back.

00:49:21.530 --> 00:49:23.510
And they're in Texas,
where I am now.

00:49:23.510 --> 00:49:25.620
And I love Texas.

00:49:25.620 --> 00:49:27.980
But in East Texas,
you know-- and I

00:49:27.980 --> 00:49:31.781
think a lot of maybe panelists
had this experience, where

00:49:31.781 --> 00:49:34.280
you meet people you didn't know,
but they're related to you.

00:49:34.280 --> 00:49:36.440
And what they want to
show you are the pictures

00:49:36.440 --> 00:49:40.100
of their children who
married white people,

00:49:40.100 --> 00:49:42.770
and their light
skinned grandchildren.

00:49:42.770 --> 00:49:46.280
And these are the things
you hold up as a trophy

00:49:46.280 --> 00:49:48.920
or as a point of pride, and
you don't see the others.

00:49:48.920 --> 00:49:51.170
I mean, so that's like
kind of a familial context,

00:49:51.170 --> 00:49:54.060
but I think the same thing
happens in our institutions.

00:49:54.060 --> 00:49:56.000
I don't think it's
an accident that when

00:49:56.000 --> 00:49:58.760
you look around institutions,
you see people in positions

00:49:58.760 --> 00:50:00.680
of power who might be Latino.

00:50:00.680 --> 00:50:02.270
That they may be fair skinned.

00:50:02.270 --> 00:50:09.920
That they may look like the
more standard ideal of beauty--

00:50:09.920 --> 00:50:11.907
European features,
whatever it might be.

00:50:11.907 --> 00:50:14.240
You know, however that idea
is constructed in our minds.

00:50:14.240 --> 00:50:16.580
And so I think there are
a lot of intersecting

00:50:16.580 --> 00:50:19.730
points on this
topic, but I really

00:50:19.730 --> 00:50:21.740
think that we could
really benefit

00:50:21.740 --> 00:50:24.980
from talking more about colorism
and color discrimination.

00:50:24.980 --> 00:50:26.630
Not just within
Latino communities--

00:50:26.630 --> 00:50:29.930
because this affects every
community, Asian, white,

00:50:29.930 --> 00:50:32.700
African-American, so
across the spectrum.

00:50:32.700 --> 00:50:35.960
But I do think that's a
really important point.

00:50:35.960 --> 00:50:37.670
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you so much.

00:50:37.670 --> 00:50:40.400
We have-- unless you
have any other points.

00:50:40.400 --> 00:50:41.400
I have one-- I think--

00:50:41.400 --> 00:50:45.585
JC, you look like you're
itching to answer that question.

00:50:45.585 --> 00:50:47.960
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: I'm so
excited about the Afro Latino

00:50:47.960 --> 00:50:48.580
movement.

00:50:48.580 --> 00:50:49.160
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: Yes?

00:50:49.160 --> 00:50:49.860
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO:
I really am.

00:50:49.860 --> 00:50:51.730
You know, as a Dominican--
and I mentioned this again--

00:50:51.730 --> 00:50:53.730
if you ever want to study
a group of people that

00:50:53.730 --> 00:50:55.580
are really conflicted,
92% of our people

00:50:55.580 --> 00:50:57.200
have African descendancy.

00:50:57.200 --> 00:50:58.700
We avoid it like
it's the plague.

00:50:58.700 --> 00:51:00.784
For us to admit that
we have black in us?

00:51:00.784 --> 00:51:01.450
Let me tell you.

00:51:01.450 --> 00:51:02.150
You know this.

00:51:02.150 --> 00:51:02.800
You know this, Daisy.

00:51:02.800 --> 00:51:04.340
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: I'm
Dominican and Puerto Rican.

00:51:04.340 --> 00:51:04.880
That's why he says.

00:51:04.880 --> 00:51:07.463
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: My kids are
too, so it's a real conflict.

00:51:07.463 --> 00:51:08.180
Think about this.

00:51:08.180 --> 00:51:11.480
We will mention every shade
before we accept blackness.

00:51:11.480 --> 00:51:13.910
We will call ourselves
oat, dark oat,

00:51:13.910 --> 00:51:17.390
burnt oat, light Indian, medium
Indian, dark Indian, light

00:51:17.390 --> 00:51:18.050
chocolate.

00:51:18.050 --> 00:51:19.039
You go down the list.

00:51:19.039 --> 00:51:21.080
You never want to be
associated with being black.

00:51:21.080 --> 00:51:24.556
And that was the concept
for a very, very long time.

00:51:24.556 --> 00:51:26.180
I grew up-- and as
I mentioned earlier,

00:51:26.180 --> 00:51:27.888
and I shared with you
that I am biracial.

00:51:27.888 --> 00:51:29.810
But my entire family is
either white or black.

00:51:29.810 --> 00:51:30.950
So we are that family.

00:51:30.950 --> 00:51:33.140
We are that little
unit of people

00:51:33.140 --> 00:51:35.210
that look like me, that
are accepted by one side

00:51:35.210 --> 00:51:36.710
but not by the other too much.

00:51:36.710 --> 00:51:38.501
And I'm sorry if you
watch and you get mad,

00:51:38.501 --> 00:51:40.590
but you really didn't
accept me, guys.

00:51:40.590 --> 00:51:42.289
But it's interesting.

00:51:42.289 --> 00:51:44.330
And I want to share
something with you, because I

00:51:44.330 --> 00:51:45.350
think history is so important.

00:51:45.350 --> 00:51:45.830
Words matter.

00:51:45.830 --> 00:51:46.413
Labels matter.

00:51:46.413 --> 00:51:47.155
I got it.

00:51:47.155 --> 00:51:48.780
There's a reason why
this is happening.

00:51:48.780 --> 00:51:50.250
There's a reason why this is.

00:51:50.250 --> 00:51:52.640
And if you study the
Latin American conquest,

00:51:52.640 --> 00:51:56.000
you soon realize how important
it was, at one point,

00:51:56.000 --> 00:52:00.960
for the Spanish landowner to
have a ratio on his plantation

00:52:00.960 --> 00:52:03.740
that would be enough
master to slave

00:52:03.740 --> 00:52:06.020
to be able to
control a rebellion.

00:52:06.020 --> 00:52:08.180
And how it was, the reality,
that there was never

00:52:08.180 --> 00:52:10.160
enough white slave masters.

00:52:10.160 --> 00:52:11.482
And it's because of that.

00:52:11.482 --> 00:52:13.220
That the white
slave master began--

00:52:13.220 --> 00:52:15.890
not accepting citizens of
Spain, because you couldn't be,

00:52:15.890 --> 00:52:17.780
but citizens of the land.

00:52:17.780 --> 00:52:20.510
And Dr. Frank Moya Pons,
who is the authority when

00:52:20.510 --> 00:52:23.030
it comes to the history
of the Dominican Republic,

00:52:23.030 --> 00:52:24.627
really writes
clearly about this.

00:52:24.627 --> 00:52:26.210
When he talks about
the fact that they

00:52:26.210 --> 00:52:29.060
were forced to accept people
that were more like them

00:52:29.060 --> 00:52:32.720
in hue, and have them want
to now be the overseers

00:52:32.720 --> 00:52:34.640
and manage the other
black folk, that

00:52:34.640 --> 00:52:37.640
created a sense of superiority
among those that appeared

00:52:37.640 --> 00:52:40.910
to be more lighter in tone,
more European in tone,

00:52:40.910 --> 00:52:43.580
and really created resentment
amongst many people that

00:52:43.580 --> 00:52:45.710
wanted their children to
be the ones on the horse.

00:52:45.710 --> 00:52:48.272
The one on the porch, the one
inside, the one not getting

00:52:48.272 --> 00:52:49.730
raped and killed
in the plantation.

00:52:49.730 --> 00:52:52.460
That reality, because
everything's historical,

00:52:52.460 --> 00:52:53.721
affected people today.

00:52:53.721 --> 00:52:55.970
And it's been ingrained in
so many Latinos not wanting

00:52:55.970 --> 00:52:56.950
to accept their blackness.

00:52:56.950 --> 00:52:58.220
I've written a lot about this.

00:52:58.220 --> 00:52:59.970
I get really excited
about this topic.

00:52:59.970 --> 00:53:03.569
So when I see African
descent Latinas no longer

00:53:03.569 --> 00:53:06.110
feel the need that they need to
have their hair a certain way

00:53:06.110 --> 00:53:07.940
and go through a
process of chemical

00:53:07.940 --> 00:53:10.610
destruction of their follicles,
and accept their blackness.

00:53:10.610 --> 00:53:12.590
And when I see them
say, I don't have

00:53:12.590 --> 00:53:14.270
to get plastic
surgery on my nose.

00:53:14.270 --> 00:53:17.380
When I hear them say, I'm black,
and I'm proud, and it's OK,

00:53:17.380 --> 00:53:19.160
and yes, you can be
black and Latino.

00:53:19.160 --> 00:53:21.410
Like you could be
a white American.

00:53:21.410 --> 00:53:23.300
Like you could be
a black Frenchmen.

00:53:23.300 --> 00:53:25.100
Like you can be a black Latino.

00:53:25.100 --> 00:53:27.860
Like we could have Ricky
Martin and David Ortiz,

00:53:27.860 --> 00:53:29.780
and they're both Latinos, right?

00:53:29.780 --> 00:53:31.580
So it's a great
thing to talk about.

00:53:31.580 --> 00:53:33.757
I'm really happy that you're
starting to write about

00:53:33.757 --> 00:53:35.090
and people are talking about it.

00:53:35.090 --> 00:53:37.220
And the Afro Latino
movement is very important.

00:53:37.220 --> 00:53:41.330
Because a sense of self
inferiority is being diluted.

00:53:41.330 --> 00:53:42.596
I'm really excited about it.

00:53:42.596 --> 00:53:43.970
