or de-funding Latino studies,
or African American studies,

01:09:02.740 --> 01:09:05.720
Pan-African studies,
Asian studies, LGBTQ

01:09:05.720 --> 01:09:08.649
and queer studies,
I mean, this is

01:09:08.649 --> 01:09:11.359
where that breaking-- that
scholarship has resided.

01:09:11.359 --> 01:09:13.100
And so there are a
number of scholars.

01:09:13.100 --> 01:09:14.733
I can give names later.

01:09:14.733 --> 01:09:16.149
But there is
scholarship out there

01:09:16.149 --> 01:09:18.670
that has talked about
precedent for these allies.

01:09:18.670 --> 01:09:19.660
And I think that--

01:09:19.660 --> 01:09:21.101
these alliances, rather.

01:09:21.101 --> 01:09:23.350
But I do think that right
now, because of the shifting

01:09:23.350 --> 01:09:26.109
demographics of the nation that
they're-- it's all the more

01:09:26.109 --> 01:09:30.160
critical that
Latinos especially,

01:09:30.160 --> 01:09:36.670
or Latinx's, especially, create
a very conscientious outreach

01:09:36.670 --> 01:09:41.600
to our brothers and sisters
who may be excluded,

01:09:41.600 --> 01:09:45.359
or may be without any
intentionality toward it from

01:09:45.359 --> 01:09:47.790
a national shifting
conversation.

01:09:47.790 --> 01:09:49.290
AMERICA FERRERA: I
would love to add

01:09:49.290 --> 01:09:51.870
to that I think leadership
really matters as well.

01:09:51.870 --> 01:09:56.550
I think convening people
who are already established,

01:09:56.550 --> 01:09:58.650
trusted voices in
their community

01:09:58.650 --> 01:10:02.460
to exemplify and model
building those bridges.

01:10:02.460 --> 01:10:06.510
My husband and I started
sort of a convening and--

01:10:06.510 --> 01:10:11.070
not "sort of"-- a convening
of influencers and people

01:10:11.070 --> 01:10:11.910
in organizations.

01:10:11.910 --> 01:10:14.550
And what we try to do
in those conversations

01:10:14.550 --> 01:10:17.370
is draw what aligns us.

01:10:17.370 --> 01:10:18.510
You know, bring that out.

01:10:18.510 --> 01:10:21.360
And to hear someone from--

01:10:21.360 --> 01:10:23.310
a co-founder of
Black Lives Matter

01:10:23.310 --> 01:10:28.770
say that DACA students showed
up for Black Lives Matter.

01:10:28.770 --> 01:10:31.740
And so Black Lives Matter,
they show up for DACA.

01:10:31.740 --> 01:10:33.500
Or DACA and Black Lives Matter.

01:10:33.500 --> 01:10:35.560
We're on the front
lines at Standing Rock,

01:10:35.560 --> 01:10:37.830
with the Native American
youth leadership.

01:10:37.830 --> 01:10:43.950
Leadership really matters and
exemplifying, especially today,

01:10:43.950 --> 01:10:46.290
that we see our
struggles inside of one

01:10:46.290 --> 01:10:48.570
another's struggles
I think really

01:10:48.570 --> 01:10:50.760
makes a difference and
matters, especially when

01:10:50.760 --> 01:10:53.430
you talk about setting
an example for our youth,

01:10:53.430 --> 01:10:55.290
and our young people,
and whether or not

01:10:55.290 --> 01:10:59.796
they can see themselves in
each other's experiences.

01:10:59.796 --> 01:11:01.170
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

01:11:01.170 --> 01:11:03.647
I'm going to move over
to the Dory for a bit.

01:11:03.647 --> 01:11:05.230
We have we have quite
a few questions,

01:11:05.230 --> 01:11:08.350
so I'll do the first two
and then move live here.

01:11:08.350 --> 01:11:10.890
The first one is from Marrissa.

01:11:10.890 --> 01:11:13.110
Using Crenshaw's theory
of intersectionality,

01:11:13.110 --> 01:11:15.720
we place excluded
groups at the center

01:11:15.720 --> 01:11:20.340
of analysis, which helps us
see that hierarchies are not

01:11:20.340 --> 01:11:22.110
absolute, but relative.

01:11:22.110 --> 01:11:24.540
How do we recognize the
matrix-like interaction

01:11:24.540 --> 01:11:27.960
of race, gender, social
class and upward mobility

01:11:27.960 --> 01:11:31.552
within the Latinx community?

01:11:31.552 --> 01:11:32.910
[LAUGHTER]

01:11:32.910 --> 01:11:34.030
These are light questions.

01:11:34.030 --> 01:11:34.863
RHONDA GONZALEZ: OK.

01:11:34.863 --> 01:11:37.560
From the professor, I'm going
to say read a lot, right?

01:11:37.560 --> 01:11:38.310
Read.

01:11:38.310 --> 01:11:39.030
Read.

01:11:39.030 --> 01:11:40.980
Read deeply.

01:11:40.980 --> 01:11:44.730
Read deeply instead
of just broadly.

01:11:44.730 --> 01:11:46.350
You know, really read deeply.

01:11:46.350 --> 01:11:49.062
But I also think that this
gets to the kind of climate

01:11:49.062 --> 01:11:51.270
that I think really pervades
our nation, as it's kind

01:11:51.270 --> 01:11:52.470
of an anti-intellectualism.

01:11:52.470 --> 01:11:55.770
And I think that embracing
the idea of intellectualism

01:11:55.770 --> 01:11:59.040
means that, of course we
deal with these complicated

01:11:59.040 --> 01:12:00.132
intersections.

01:12:00.132 --> 01:12:01.590
That not only do
we deal with them,

01:12:01.590 --> 01:12:03.930
but we actually
should thrive on them.

01:12:03.930 --> 01:12:05.400
I often tell my
students, because I

01:12:05.400 --> 01:12:07.740
teach African history,
that, in this classroom,

01:12:07.740 --> 01:12:11.340
we embody a Nigerian
cafe environment.

01:12:11.340 --> 01:12:13.440
So, you know, if you were
to walk into a coffee

01:12:13.440 --> 01:12:16.890
shop in Nigeria, people are
engaged in a really vigorous

01:12:16.890 --> 01:12:19.260
discussion and
debate, but really

01:12:19.260 --> 01:12:22.350
for not so much winning
a debate, right?

01:12:22.350 --> 01:12:25.740
But for the collective
understanding and the growth

01:12:25.740 --> 01:12:26.970
that comes out of debates.

01:12:26.970 --> 01:12:28.657
So I really think
that that's one way.

01:12:28.657 --> 01:12:30.240
AMERICA FERRERA: An
idea came to mind.

01:12:30.240 --> 01:12:32.820
You know, I heard earlier
that, within Google, you

01:12:32.820 --> 01:12:34.500
have all these groups.

01:12:34.500 --> 01:12:36.780
You have HOLA, you
have the black network.

01:12:36.780 --> 01:12:39.960
And that's an opportunity
inside of Google for you all

01:12:39.960 --> 01:12:42.870
to start building bridges,
and finding intersectionality,

01:12:42.870 --> 01:12:45.750
and showing up for one
another's conversations,

01:12:45.750 --> 01:12:51.445
and modeling how we begin
to find what aligns us.

01:12:51.445 --> 01:12:52.820
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

01:12:52.820 --> 01:12:53.820
ANDREW HERRERA: Yeah, I
was just going to add--

01:12:53.820 --> 01:12:55.890
I mean, that's a great segue.

01:12:55.890 --> 01:12:58.470
I mean, one of our
most successful pieces

01:12:58.470 --> 01:13:02.270
was on how Filipinos
are our cousins,

01:13:02.270 --> 01:13:03.300
are our Latino cousins.

01:13:03.300 --> 01:13:04.740
And actually, it went viral.

01:13:04.740 --> 01:13:07.830
And those are the types
of things where, you know,

01:13:07.830 --> 01:13:12.210
what aligns us is actually what
is able to create a stronger

01:13:12.210 --> 01:13:12.840
message.

01:13:12.840 --> 01:13:16.920
So, and, you know, I think
I would continue down

01:13:16.920 --> 01:13:19.170
that road of--

01:13:19.170 --> 01:13:22.740
I think there's a lot of
youth that are trying to,

01:13:22.740 --> 01:13:25.260
whether it be on
political issues,

01:13:25.260 --> 01:13:27.830
to kind of depoliticize
the conversation.

01:13:27.830 --> 01:13:29.020
It's happening in music.

01:13:29.020 --> 01:13:32.400
It's happening in people
creating great content, where

01:13:32.400 --> 01:13:36.790
people are collaborating and
adding their own nuance to it.

01:13:36.790 --> 01:13:40.920
And so I think, in terms of--

01:13:40.920 --> 01:13:43.980
at Google, I think
you could also--

01:13:43.980 --> 01:13:45.630
I wanted to enter on
the last question.

01:13:45.630 --> 01:13:47.550
I think you guys
should definitely

01:13:47.550 --> 01:13:48.600
feel entrepreneurial.

01:13:48.600 --> 01:13:51.330
Don't wait for the
organization to change.

01:13:51.330 --> 01:13:53.430
Be part of the change.

01:13:53.430 --> 01:13:57.200
And whether that be within
an official Google--

01:13:57.200 --> 01:14:02.430
you know, Google organization,
you can do that on your own

01:14:02.430 --> 01:14:03.980
and be entrepreneurial
with that.

01:14:03.980 --> 01:14:05.760
And, you know, I think--

01:14:05.760 --> 01:14:09.420
we're a culture that's
pretty scrappy in terms

01:14:09.420 --> 01:14:13.110
of how we evolve and how
we achieve great things.

01:14:13.110 --> 01:14:17.200
I think taking that into--

01:14:17.200 --> 01:14:19.600
as a way to create
change, I think,

01:14:19.600 --> 01:14:20.960
was something I would recommend.

01:14:20.960 --> 01:14:21.420
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

01:14:21.420 --> 01:14:23.060
Googlers, get scrappy.

01:14:23.060 --> 01:14:25.080
All right?

01:14:25.080 --> 01:14:28.590
Selena, from Austin, asks,
how do we support each other

01:14:28.590 --> 01:14:31.890
within the Latinx community and
across the various backgrounds

01:14:31.890 --> 01:14:33.420
that make up Latinx
in a way that

01:14:33.420 --> 01:14:36.390
allows us to break down the
pre-established structures

01:14:36.390 --> 01:14:37.418
of discrimination?

01:14:41.154 --> 01:14:42.820
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO:
I don't understand.

01:14:42.820 --> 01:14:45.670
The question regarding
discrimination in the United

01:14:45.670 --> 01:14:46.679
States, and how it's--

01:14:46.679 --> 01:14:48.220
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Across-- yeah,

01:14:48.220 --> 01:14:50.200
how do we support each
other within the community,

01:14:50.200 --> 01:14:51.700
and across our
various backgrounds--

01:14:51.700 --> 01:14:54.179
intersectionalities, I'm
going to understand--

01:14:54.179 --> 01:14:56.470
that allows us to break down
pre-established structures

01:14:56.470 --> 01:14:57.714
of discrimination?

01:14:57.714 --> 01:15:00.130
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: Well, I
think there's a lot going on.

01:15:00.130 --> 01:15:00.610
I do.

01:15:00.610 --> 01:15:01.780
I think there are
a lot of movements.

01:15:01.780 --> 01:15:03.160
I think that the
election of-- and I

01:15:03.160 --> 01:15:05.118
know that there are lot
of people that disagree

01:15:05.118 --> 01:15:06.457
with me, especially on my side.

01:15:06.457 --> 01:15:08.290
I think that the election
of President Obama

01:15:08.290 --> 01:15:12.070
did a lot to tear down some
of those walls of things

01:15:12.070 --> 01:15:14.614
that we thought were
impossible, of groups

01:15:14.614 --> 01:15:16.780
of people that we thought
would never come together.

01:15:16.780 --> 01:15:18.940
I think that a lot
has already happened.

01:15:18.940 --> 01:15:20.230
A lot has been written.

01:15:20.230 --> 01:15:21.700
A lot has been discussed.

01:15:21.700 --> 01:15:23.560
And I think we can
learn from that.

01:15:23.560 --> 01:15:25.690
And I think we
can say, you know,

01:15:25.690 --> 01:15:30.320
this election of President
Obama has created an environment

01:15:30.320 --> 01:15:33.010
where a lot of the
vestiges of discrimination

01:15:33.010 --> 01:15:34.420
may be breaking down.

01:15:34.420 --> 01:15:36.350
So I know he's not
in office anymore,

01:15:36.350 --> 01:15:39.246
and I know a lot of my friends
are very sad about that.

01:15:39.246 --> 01:15:40.870
But I think it's an
opportunity for you

01:15:40.870 --> 01:15:43.536
to see, what is the vestige of--
what is the legacy of President

01:15:43.536 --> 01:15:44.140
Obama?

01:15:44.140 --> 01:15:45.820
And I'm asking you
as a Republican.

01:15:45.820 --> 01:15:47.910
What is the legacy behind--

01:15:47.910 --> 01:15:49.120
is it just Obamacare?

01:15:49.120 --> 01:15:50.500
I think there's more.

01:15:50.500 --> 01:15:52.210
I think that the
legacy has to be

01:15:52.210 --> 01:15:55.600
how many of these walls
that we had before

01:15:55.600 --> 01:15:57.090
may not be perfectly torn down.

01:15:57.090 --> 01:15:59.110
There may be some
bricks up there still.

01:15:59.110 --> 01:16:00.910
But a lot of them
have come down.

01:16:00.910 --> 01:16:03.850
And I think that the person
that asked the question

01:16:03.850 --> 01:16:07.390
has to just realize that
we are in a new age.

01:16:07.390 --> 01:16:09.700
And there is discrimination,
but not even close

01:16:09.700 --> 01:16:10.670
to how it used to be.

01:16:10.670 --> 01:16:11.930
I think

01:16:11.930 --> 01:16:15.310
AMERICA FERRERA: I think on
a very, very basic level,

01:16:15.310 --> 01:16:18.160
it's that you have to do
something for someone else,

01:16:18.160 --> 01:16:19.120
wherever you are.

01:16:19.120 --> 01:16:21.430
If you've reached a position
of influence or power

01:16:21.430 --> 01:16:24.059
or privilege, even if that means
you've found a way to graduate

01:16:24.059 --> 01:16:26.350
high school, in a community
where people don't know how

01:16:26.350 --> 01:16:29.590
to graduate high school,
or can't get through it,

01:16:29.590 --> 01:16:32.980
turn around and figure out
a way to open that door

01:16:32.980 --> 01:16:36.910
or remove a barrier for someone
else to come in behind you.

01:16:36.910 --> 01:16:40.930
I know my career would
not have been possible

01:16:40.930 --> 01:16:43.750
five years before it began.

01:16:43.750 --> 01:16:45.910
You know, I came
around and I had--

01:16:45.910 --> 01:16:50.350
it was a perfect confluence
of a million things

01:16:50.350 --> 01:16:52.870
that allowed me to get to step
in and take that opportunity.

01:16:52.870 --> 01:16:55.078
That doesn't mean there
weren't hundreds or thousands

01:16:55.078 --> 01:16:57.310
of other people who could
have just as easily taken

01:16:57.310 --> 01:16:58.510
that opportunity.

01:16:58.510 --> 01:17:02.020
And now I have access because
other people created access

01:17:02.020 --> 01:17:02.860
for me.

01:17:02.860 --> 01:17:06.730
And so wherever we are, in
whatever industry we work in,

01:17:06.730 --> 01:17:10.000
whatever privileges we've
had in our lives, especially

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:12.640
people who work
at Google, we have

01:17:12.640 --> 01:17:16.547
to understand that
we are the ones that

01:17:16.547 --> 01:17:18.130
are going to be able
to open that door

01:17:18.130 --> 01:17:19.480
for that next generation.

01:17:19.480 --> 01:17:20.855
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

01:17:20.855 --> 01:17:21.355
Yes.

01:17:21.355 --> 01:17:23.280
