01:17:25.129 --> 01:17:26.670
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Live question.

01:17:26.670 --> 01:17:28.390
AUDIENCE: Hi.

01:17:28.390 --> 01:17:32.220
So I've noticed, at least in
the kind of white culture,

01:17:32.220 --> 01:17:35.910
if there's an indigenous
person from Mexico in the US,

01:17:35.910 --> 01:17:38.370
they're a Latino, Latinx.

01:17:38.370 --> 01:17:41.340
If they're an indigenous
person from America,

01:17:41.340 --> 01:17:42.600
they're a Native American.

01:17:42.600 --> 01:17:43.558
And they're not Latino.

01:17:45.150 --> 01:17:47.760
Why does Native American
seem to be this kind

01:17:47.760 --> 01:17:50.850
of different group from Latino?

01:17:50.850 --> 01:17:52.620
Do you agree with that?

01:17:52.620 --> 01:17:53.700
I mean, I don't--

01:17:53.700 --> 01:17:55.600
as I said, that's kind
of the stereotype.

01:17:55.600 --> 01:17:58.066
But do you see Native
Americans as part of Latino?

01:17:58.066 --> 01:18:00.316
JUAN CARLOS POLANCO: I am a
firm believer that you can

01:18:00.316 --> 01:18:02.317
be many things and be Latino.

01:18:02.317 --> 01:18:04.650
And I think that when you
think about Native Americans--

01:18:04.650 --> 01:18:06.150
and I have this
discussion in my class.

01:18:06.150 --> 01:18:08.733
When you think about the Native
American nations that existed,

01:18:08.733 --> 01:18:12.270
and how so many of
them are located

01:18:12.270 --> 01:18:14.460
in what we call the
United States today,

01:18:14.460 --> 01:18:16.920
at one point were part
of the Spanish conquest,

01:18:16.920 --> 01:18:20.550
those people today are Latinos,
and they are Native American.

01:18:20.550 --> 01:18:21.880
And you can be both.

01:18:21.880 --> 01:18:23.920
I don't think it's
one or the other.

01:18:23.920 --> 01:18:27.060
I think that it's time that we
as Latin Americans or Americans

01:18:27.060 --> 01:18:29.844
of Latino descent understand
that there are millions

01:18:29.844 --> 01:18:31.260
of our people in
the United States

01:18:31.260 --> 01:18:33.240
that are in fact
Native Americans.

01:18:33.240 --> 01:18:35.560
They may speak Spanish
and have Spanish surnames,

01:18:35.560 --> 01:18:36.940
and share in our
Latino identity,

01:18:36.940 --> 01:18:39.150
but I think both of
them are coexistent.

01:18:39.150 --> 01:18:39.600
AMERICA FERRERA:
You know, I think

01:18:39.600 --> 01:18:41.641
this goes back to sort of
one of the first things

01:18:41.641 --> 01:18:44.610
we were talking about, like
identification, and labels,

01:18:44.610 --> 01:18:45.480
and why they matter.

01:18:45.480 --> 01:18:47.700
And, you know, the
truth is, as a Latina,

01:18:47.700 --> 01:18:51.690
I never thought to think of
myself as an indigenous person.

01:18:51.690 --> 01:18:54.930
And I've actually
heard of conversations

01:18:54.930 --> 01:18:59.040
amongst Native American thought
leaders about this concept

01:18:59.040 --> 01:19:04.440
of indigenousness and how Latino
Americans have been completely

01:19:04.440 --> 01:19:07.190
ripped from their indigenousness
and don't claim that

01:19:07.190 --> 01:19:12.330
and don't identify
themselves, and how powerful

01:19:12.330 --> 01:19:16.380
would that be if we could
find a way to merge, you know,

01:19:16.380 --> 01:19:21.030
our efforts and see ourselves
in our Native American brothers

01:19:21.030 --> 01:19:27.210
and sisters, as related
through our indigenousness?

01:19:27.210 --> 01:19:31.260
And I think there's an
incredibly powerful thought

01:19:31.260 --> 01:19:35.070
in there, that I've only
recently begun to even

01:19:35.070 --> 01:19:43.710
hear be verbalized outside of
academic or scholarly worlds,

01:19:43.710 --> 01:19:46.260
where I'm sure it probably
has been discussed.

01:19:46.260 --> 01:19:49.470
ANDREW HERRERA: I mean, there
are indigenous communities

01:19:49.470 --> 01:19:51.990
that I would say, in Latin
America and South America,

01:19:51.990 --> 01:19:54.950
that wouldn't identify
themselves as Latinos.

01:19:54.950 --> 01:19:56.700
So I think that's one--
you know, actually

01:19:56.700 --> 01:20:01.790
to be accurate about kind
of that that labeling again.

01:20:01.790 --> 01:20:05.040
So I think we need to
understand that piece.

01:20:05.040 --> 01:20:06.870
You know, obviously,
from my skin color,

01:20:06.870 --> 01:20:10.470
there is an
indigenous side of me.

01:20:10.470 --> 01:20:12.394
But there are communities
that still don't.

01:20:12.394 --> 01:20:14.310
So I think we need to
be conscious of the fact

01:20:14.310 --> 01:20:17.670
that I think there's that same
issue that Native Americans

01:20:17.670 --> 01:20:21.810
have that also exist in Latin
America, where they actually

01:20:21.810 --> 01:20:22.890
don't even speak Spanish.

01:20:22.890 --> 01:20:28.380
So they've actually continued
to live out their independence.

01:20:28.380 --> 01:20:30.970
In Ecuador and Peru,
they speak Quechua.

01:20:30.970 --> 01:20:34.977
And that's a language that is
not at all tied to Spanish.

01:20:34.977 --> 01:20:36.060
RHONDA GONZALEZ: I think--

01:20:36.060 --> 01:20:37.920
the small comment
I'll make I think

01:20:37.920 --> 01:20:40.740
is about the politics
of indigeneity

01:20:40.740 --> 01:20:43.685
and the claims of it is tied
to the nation, and the nation's

01:20:43.685 --> 01:20:44.310
history, right?

01:20:44.310 --> 01:20:48.960
So in our context
here in North America,

01:20:48.960 --> 01:20:51.750
the idea of indigeneity
and indigenous populations,

01:20:51.750 --> 01:20:56.370
Native Americans, I mean, this
is their land that was taken,

01:20:56.370 --> 01:20:57.330
given back.

01:20:57.330 --> 01:21:00.580
Now they're, for all
intents and purposes,

01:21:00.580 --> 01:21:05.280
in an apartheid structure in
the state, in this country.

01:21:05.280 --> 01:21:09.630
But I also think the politics
of being Latina or Latino,

01:21:09.630 --> 01:21:13.200
and within that
context, has created--

01:21:13.200 --> 01:21:15.030
part of what we're
really talking about

01:21:15.030 --> 01:21:18.120
is that many Latinos
feel like they

01:21:18.120 --> 01:21:20.700
live in this sort
of liminal space,

01:21:20.700 --> 01:21:23.790
or the interstitial spaces,
if you get into theory

01:21:23.790 --> 01:21:25.440
about what that means.

01:21:25.440 --> 01:21:28.380
And that is neither being
of here or there, right?

01:21:28.380 --> 01:21:30.970
So you're kind of
like without a nation.

01:21:30.970 --> 01:21:34.770
And so I think part of this
complexity and nuance--

01:21:34.770 --> 01:21:38.460
because we are everywhere,
and yet this is not ours.

01:21:38.460 --> 01:21:40.410
And especially when
we have leadership

01:21:40.410 --> 01:21:44.190
at the political level, speaking
as if we don't belong here,

01:21:44.190 --> 01:21:48.150
even though, for many of
us, our roots go very deep.

01:21:48.150 --> 01:21:51.404
So I think there's-- it's a
really complicated answer,

01:21:51.404 --> 01:21:53.820
but I do think it's tied up
in the politics of the history

01:21:53.820 --> 01:21:55.345
of this nation in particular.

01:21:55.345 --> 01:21:56.720
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you.

01:21:56.720 --> 01:21:57.930
