externally, where

01:30:49.140 --> 01:30:51.090
you might see so
much more coverage

01:30:51.090 --> 01:30:52.620
on the black movements.

01:30:52.620 --> 01:30:55.200
Or it's just much
louder and amplified.

01:30:55.200 --> 01:30:56.820
And that might just
be a perception,

01:30:56.820 --> 01:30:58.660
but perception is reality.

01:30:58.660 --> 01:31:00.531
So how do we empower--

01:31:00.531 --> 01:31:02.280
and sometimes it might
be cultural, right?

01:31:02.280 --> 01:31:04.794
We try not to create
a lot of waves,

01:31:04.794 --> 01:31:06.210
or ruffle too many
feathers, or we

01:31:06.210 --> 01:31:09.150
try to be much more
collaborative about it, where

01:31:09.150 --> 01:31:13.180
some communities just do
it and apologize later.

01:31:13.180 --> 01:31:15.990
How do we get our
Latinos to really

01:31:15.990 --> 01:31:19.080
kind of take that stance,
and just amplify that voice,

01:31:19.080 --> 01:31:22.312
and not be worried about
the backlash, like you said,

01:31:22.312 --> 01:31:24.020
where they kind of
just take that stance?

01:31:24.020 --> 01:31:26.340
So I'm just trying
to grapple with,

01:31:26.340 --> 01:31:29.730
how do we get our Latino group,
the HOLA, to kind of really

01:31:29.730 --> 01:31:32.760
amplify that voice the
way that their other peers

01:31:32.760 --> 01:31:34.222
and colleagues are doing?

01:31:36.914 --> 01:31:39.080
RHONDA GONZALEZ: That's a
really beautiful question,

01:31:39.080 --> 01:31:39.860
I have to say.

01:31:39.860 --> 01:31:44.360
It's a really, really important
one, and I love those pants,

01:31:44.360 --> 01:31:45.586
and I'm taking them from her.

01:31:45.586 --> 01:31:46.460
No, I'm just kidding.

01:31:46.460 --> 01:31:47.690
They're great.

01:31:47.690 --> 01:31:49.537
So--

01:31:49.537 --> 01:31:52.120
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ: In Latino
culture, you say [INAUDIBLE].

01:31:52.120 --> 01:31:54.203
Which means that, anytime
you want to borrow them.

01:31:54.203 --> 01:31:56.720
RHONDA GONZALEZ: OK, OK.

01:31:56.720 --> 01:31:58.970
But I think part
of that question

01:31:58.970 --> 01:32:03.650
about being emboldened, and
maybe being a little bit

01:32:03.650 --> 01:32:06.350
careful, and trepidatious
is anchored in the fact

01:32:06.350 --> 01:32:08.060
that, in some ways,
we have privilege.

01:32:08.060 --> 01:32:09.656
In some ways, we
are not of here.

01:32:09.656 --> 01:32:11.280
Because we talk about
that [INAUDIBLE].

01:32:11.280 --> 01:32:14.240
So it's like a very
precarious kind of history

01:32:14.240 --> 01:32:16.430
that we all, I think--

01:32:16.430 --> 01:32:19.580
at least when we reach a
certain level of consciousness

01:32:19.580 --> 01:32:22.790
or understanding, that
if we're too loud,

01:32:22.790 --> 01:32:26.290
there might be backlash
against undocumented friends,

01:32:26.290 --> 01:32:27.360
their communities.

01:32:27.360 --> 01:32:29.870
Or maybe people
will talk about how,

01:32:29.870 --> 01:32:31.400
you're not from here anyway.

01:32:31.400 --> 01:32:33.590
I mean, even though
we may be of here.

01:32:33.590 --> 01:32:38.860
But I also-- and then, with
black history, for all of its--

01:32:38.860 --> 01:32:41.180
you know, the awful
tragedy of it--

01:32:41.180 --> 01:32:43.160
there is a collective
identity anchored

01:32:43.160 --> 01:32:45.691
in that experience of the
transatlantic slave trade,

01:32:45.691 --> 01:32:46.190
right?

01:32:46.190 --> 01:32:49.380
And for people who are
descendants of that.

01:32:49.380 --> 01:32:51.530
And so there is a
collective identity

01:32:51.530 --> 01:32:54.470
shaped by that long enduring
history which is very powerful.

01:32:54.470 --> 01:32:57.470
Whereas we're talking
about 26 identities

01:32:57.470 --> 01:32:59.480
that we talk about
that are in conflict.

01:32:59.480 --> 01:33:02.240
And that's not to say
Africans aren't diverse,

01:33:02.240 --> 01:33:05.540
or even in that original
experience of 400 years ago

01:33:05.540 --> 01:33:06.484
and onward.

01:33:06.484 --> 01:33:08.150
But there is something
about the history

01:33:08.150 --> 01:33:09.440
that needs to be
understood, I think,

01:33:09.440 --> 01:33:10.481
in that collective voice.

01:33:10.481 --> 01:33:11.810
And the other thing is that--

01:33:11.810 --> 01:33:14.450
maybe you touched on this,
the idea of respectability?

01:33:14.450 --> 01:33:16.460
You know, like not
wanting to step on toes

01:33:16.460 --> 01:33:18.110
and maybe being demure.

01:33:18.110 --> 01:33:21.770
And I think that, from what
I've seen in not just the Black

01:33:21.770 --> 01:33:24.290
Lives Matter movement of
the last couple of years.

01:33:24.290 --> 01:33:27.200
But, you know, if you go back
to read Du Bois and more,

01:33:27.200 --> 01:33:30.326
you see that there
is a certain idea of,

01:33:30.326 --> 01:33:31.700
if we're going to
be respectable,

01:33:31.700 --> 01:33:33.534
we're not really pushing
against status quo.

01:33:33.534 --> 01:33:35.325
And if we're going to
push against status--

01:33:35.325 --> 01:33:37.700
we need to push against
status quo if we want change.

01:33:37.700 --> 01:33:40.582
And that's really
just the bottom line.

01:33:40.582 --> 01:33:42.040
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
America, you

01:33:42.040 --> 01:33:42.910
look like you want
to say something.

01:33:42.910 --> 01:33:44.993
AMERICA FERRERA: Yeah, I
do want to say something.

01:33:44.993 --> 01:33:49.480
You know, I think too what's
so hard about right now

01:33:49.480 --> 01:33:53.440
is that we're labeling things
political which actually

01:33:53.440 --> 01:33:54.850
are not just political.

01:33:54.850 --> 01:33:57.860
They're about value systems,
and they're about humanity.

01:33:57.860 --> 01:34:02.470
And I think the more we can
message the values and say,

01:34:02.470 --> 01:34:04.120
you know, it's one
thing to ask Google

01:34:04.120 --> 01:34:06.130
to take a stance on
immigration reform,

01:34:06.130 --> 01:34:10.090
it's another thing to ask Google
to stand up for the kids who

01:34:10.090 --> 01:34:11.920
are being bullied
in their schools,

01:34:11.920 --> 01:34:14.380
for the violence
that is happening

01:34:14.380 --> 01:34:15.670
towards our communities.

01:34:15.670 --> 01:34:19.820
Regardless of intent
of the conversations,

01:34:19.820 --> 01:34:23.350
the outcome is such that
people feel emboldened

01:34:23.350 --> 01:34:26.860
to attack our children
in schools, verbally

01:34:26.860 --> 01:34:31.000
or physically, and we can't
stand for that value system.

01:34:31.000 --> 01:34:34.390
And I think that is where
our alliances help us.

01:34:34.390 --> 01:34:35.870
There is safety in numbers.

01:34:35.870 --> 01:34:39.430
So if it's not just the
Latino group saying,

01:34:39.430 --> 01:34:42.770
Google, we want you to stand
up for our communities,

01:34:42.770 --> 01:34:43.660
find alliances.

01:34:43.660 --> 01:34:44.950
Because you know what?

01:34:44.950 --> 01:34:46.596
Muslim kids are
being attacked, too.

01:34:46.596 --> 01:34:48.220
And black kids are
being attacked, too.

01:34:48.220 --> 01:34:49.990
And gay kids are
being attacked, too.

01:34:49.990 --> 01:34:52.630
So finding the
strength in numbers

01:34:52.630 --> 01:34:55.180
and emboldening yourselves
around your value system,

01:34:55.180 --> 01:34:58.420
and then asking Google
to make a decision

01:34:58.420 --> 01:35:00.100
about where their values lie.

01:35:00.100 --> 01:35:02.800
And try to remove the political
out of it, which is nearly

01:35:02.800 --> 01:35:04.730
impossible in this day and age.

01:35:04.730 --> 01:35:07.960
But I think we are at an
unprecedented moment in history

01:35:07.960 --> 01:35:10.840
where it's about humanity.

01:35:10.840 --> 01:35:12.850
And we can talk around
politics all we want.

01:35:12.850 --> 01:35:16.440
But at the end of the
day, people's lives

01:35:16.440 --> 01:35:18.820
have been made vulnerable.

01:35:18.820 --> 01:35:23.280
And what Google
does today matters.

01:35:23.280 --> 01:35:26.280
What Google and corporations
and companies like it,

01:35:26.280 --> 01:35:29.880
where they stand and how they
choose to use their influence

01:35:29.880 --> 01:35:33.000
and voice, will define
the world that we

01:35:33.000 --> 01:35:34.890
live in in 15 and 20
years, and the world

01:35:34.890 --> 01:35:36.030
that our kids grow up in.

01:35:36.030 --> 01:35:39.450
And holding them to
their value system.

01:35:39.450 --> 01:35:40.950
And you're going
to piss people off.

01:35:40.950 --> 01:35:43.136
And it's not going
to be happy go lucky,

01:35:43.136 --> 01:35:44.760
you know, let's all
sit around and have

01:35:44.760 --> 01:35:45.760
a conversation about it.

01:35:45.760 --> 01:35:48.360
You're going to have
to be willing to know

01:35:48.360 --> 01:35:51.300
that not everyone is going
to be happy about it.

01:35:51.300 --> 01:35:53.008
DAISY AUGER-DOMINGUEZ:
Thank you so much.

01:35:53.008 --> 01:35:54.030
[APPLAUSE]

01:35:54.030 --> 01:35:56.910
We are well above our time,
so we're going to close.

01:35:56.910 --> 01:35:57.990
I think that--

01:35:57.990 --> 01:36:03.360
I'm deeply thankful,
grateful for you to have come

01:36:03.360 --> 01:36:05.790
and helped us have
this conversation

01:36:05.790 --> 01:36:08.910
with Google, and eventually
outside of Google.

01:36:08.910 --> 01:36:10.770
I think what we've
heard, consistently

01:36:10.770 --> 01:36:13.590
and repeatedly, is
that words matter.

01:36:13.590 --> 01:36:14.790
Labels matter.

01:36:14.790 --> 01:36:16.320
Values matter.

01:36:16.320 --> 01:36:22.230
We are at a really critical and
exciting time for the Latino,

01:36:22.230 --> 01:36:24.690
Hispanic, Chicano.

01:36:24.690 --> 01:36:28.080
Whatever whatever name we
want to use, but this richly

01:36:28.080 --> 01:36:31.165
diverse community, there
is tremendous pride,

01:36:31.165 --> 01:36:32.790
and there's tremendous
influence that's

01:36:32.790 --> 01:36:35.310
coming from this community.

01:36:35.310 --> 01:36:37.560
As Googlers, we're
incredibly privileged,

01:36:37.560 --> 01:36:39.540
and we struggle
with our privilege.

01:36:39.540 --> 01:36:42.467
But it's also a privilege that
we want to share and expand.

01:36:42.467 --> 01:36:44.550
And we have unique
opportunities and great lessons

01:36:44.550 --> 01:36:46.080
that we've learned here today.

01:36:49.320 --> 01:36:51.450
As I'm as I'm looking
through my notes,

01:36:51.450 --> 01:36:53.730
I'm thinking about the
challenges of bringing together

01:36:53.730 --> 01:36:54.229
one--

01:36:54.229 --> 01:36:55.680
you know, 26
different identities

01:36:55.680 --> 01:36:56.970
into one shared platform.

01:36:56.970 --> 01:36:59.140
But the opportunities
that come from that.

01:36:59.140 --> 01:37:01.840
And I know that
we're ready for that.

01:37:01.840 --> 01:37:07.410
And so I want to thank America,
JC, Andrew, Dr. Gonzalez.

01:37:07.410 --> 01:37:09.780
Thank you so much, on
behalf of all Googlers here.

01:37:09.780 --> 01:37:11.700
And we hope to continue
this conversation.

01:37:11.700 --> 01:37:16.850
[APPLAUSE]

